                                <div class="main-content" >
                                    <section data-title="Introduction"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec1-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec1"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">1 </span>Introduction</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec1-content"><p>Given the enormous and unprecedented amount of distributed data available today, it is no surprise that Federated Learning (FL) has received considerable attention across a range of applications. Consequently, FL has been utilized in applications across various sectors such as transportation, health, insurance and banking, Industrial and IoT-based applications, etc. FL is associated with a high degree of reliability while managing massive amounts of data and applications and this has generated a lot of research interest in pertinent areas. Among them, the primary areas of research surrounding FL have been focused on the technical challenges, the machine learning models, system modelling and design, privacy and security, data management, resource management, to name a few. In addition to such work, a number of related surveys addressing various aspects of FL have also been conducted and referred to since the very beginning. A summary of previously published studies, along with the categories of related surveys, and their focus points have been presented in Table <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Tab1">1</a>.</p><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-1"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab1" data-test="table-caption">Table 1 Summary of existing surveys</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/tables/1" aria-label="Full size table 1"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><p>As can be observed, the above surveys have addressed various aspects of FL. To elaborate, the surveys in Li et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020a" title="Li T, Sahu AK, Talwalkar A, Smith V (2020a) Federated learning: challenges, methods, and future directions. IEEE Signal Process Mag 37(3):50–60. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/MSP.2020.2975749&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR64" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e697">2020a</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference b" title="Li L, Fan Y, Lin K-Y (2020b) A Survey on federated learning. In: 2020 IEEE 16th international conference on control &amp; automation (ICCA), pp 791–796. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICCA51439.2020.9264412&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 1948-3457" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR73" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e700">b</a>), Mammen (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Mammen PM (2021) Federated learning: opportunities and challenges. &#xA;                  arXiv:2101.05428&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR94" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e703">2021</a>), Abdulrahman et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Abdulrahman S, Tout H, Ould-Slimane H, Mourad A, Talhi C, Guizani M (2021a) A survey on federated learning: the journey from centralized to distributed on-site learning and beyond. IEEE Internet Things J 8(7):5476–5497. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2020.3030072&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR1" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e706">2021a</a>), Zhang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Zhang C, Xie Y, Bai H, Yu B, Li W, Gao Y (2021a) A survey on federated learning. Knowl-Based Syst 216:106775. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.knosys.2021.106775&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR176" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e709">2021a</a>), Rahman et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Rahman KMJ, Ahmed F, Akhter N, Hasan M, Amin R, Aziz KE, Islam AKMM, Mukta MSH, Islam AKMN (2021) Challenges, applications and design aspects of federated learning: a survey. IEEE Access 9:124682–124700. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ACCESS.2021.3111118&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR117" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e713">2021</a>) were focused on the various challenges, opportunities, and future directions of Federated Learning. The surveys in Xia et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Xia Q, Ye W, Tao Z, Wu J, Li Q (2021) A survey of federated learning for edge computing: Research problems and solutions. High-Confidence Comput 1(1):100008. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.hcc.2021.100008&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR154" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e716">2021</a>), Lim et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Lim WYB, Luong NC, Hoang DT, Jiao Y, Liang Y-C, Yang Q, Niyato D, Miao C (2020) Federated learning in mobile edge networks: a comprehensive survey. IEEE Commun Surv Tutor 22(3):2031–2063. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/COMST.2020.2986024&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR77" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e719">2020</a>), Nguyen et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021c" title="Nguyen DC, Ding M, Pathirana PN, Seneviratne A, Li J, Vincent Poor H (2021c) Federated learning for internet of things: a comprehensive survey. IEEE Commun Surv Tutor 23(3):1622–1658. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/COMST.2021.3075439&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR101" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e722">2021c</a>), Imteaj et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Imteaj A, Thakker U, Wang S, Li J, Amini MH (2022) A survey on federated learning for resource-constrained IoT devices. IEEE Internet Things J 9(1):1–24. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2021.3095077&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR49" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e725">2022</a>), Aledhari et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Aledhari M, Razzak R, Parizi RM, Saeed F (2020) Federated learning: a survey on enabling technologies, protocols, and applications. IEEE Access 8:140699–140725. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ACCESS.2020.3013541&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR4" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e728">2020</a>) discussed edge computing, the Internet of Things (IoT), enabling technologies, solutions, and opportunities. The surveys in Li et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Li Q, Wen Z, Wu Z, Hu S, Wang N, Li Y, Liu X, He B (2021a) A survey on federated learning systems: vision, hype and reality for data privacy and protection. IEEE Trans Knowl Data Eng. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TKDE.2021.3124599&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR65" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e732">2021a</a>), Mothukuri et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Mothukuri V, Parizi RM, Pouriyeh S, Huang Y, Dehghantanha A, Srivastava G (2021) A survey on security and privacy of federated learning. Futur Gener Comput Syst 115:619–640. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.future.2020.10.007&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR97" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e735">2021</a>), Lyu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Lyu L, Yu H, Yang Q (2020) Threats to federated learning: a survey. &#xA;                  arXiv:2003.02133&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR91" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e738">2020</a>), Kulkarni et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Kulkarni V, Kulkarni M, Pant, A (2020) Survey of personalization techniques for federated learning. In: 2020 fourth world conference on smart trends in systems, security and sustainability (WorldS4), pp 794–797. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/WorldS450073.2020.9210355&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR59" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e741">2020</a>), Blanco-Justicia et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Blanco-Justicia A, Domingo-Ferrer J, Martínez S, Sánchez D, Flanagan A, Tan KE (2021) Achieving security and privacy in federated learning systems: survey, research challenges and future directions. Eng Appl Artif Intell 106:104468. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.engappai.2021.104468&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR9" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e744">2021</a>), Ghimire and Rawat (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Ghimire B, Rawat DB (2022) Recent advances on federated learning for cybersecurity and cybersecurity for federated learning for Internet of Things. IEEE Internet Things J 9(11):8229–8249. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2022.3150363&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR33" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e747">2022</a>), Yin et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Yin X, Zhu Y, Hu J (2021) A comprehensive survey of privacy-preserving federated learning: a taxonomy, review, and future directions. ACM Comput Surv 54(6):131–113136. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3460427&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR168" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e751">2021</a>), Ouadrhiri and Abdelhadi (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Ouadrhiri AE, Abdelhadi A (2022) Differential privacy for deep and federated learning: a survey. IEEE Access 10:22359–22380. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ACCESS.2022.3151670&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR107" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e754">2022</a>), Li et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022b" title="Li D, Han D, Weng T-H, Zheng Z, Li H, Liu H, Castiglione A, Li K-C (2022b) Blockchain for federated learning toward secure distributed machine learning systems: a systemic survey. Soft Comput 26(9):4423–4440. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s00500-021-06496-5&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR68" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e757">2022b</a>) discussed the areas of data protection, privacy, security, cybersecurity, secure distributed Learning, and various FL techniques. In a similar vein, Kholod et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Kholod I, Yanaki E, Fomichev D, Shalugin E, Novikova E, Filippov E, Nordlund M (2020) Open-source federated learning frameworks for IoT: a comparative review and analysis. Sensors 21(1):167. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.3390/s21010167&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR55" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e760">2020</a>) presented a survey of open-source FL frameworks for IoT, and the surveys in Liu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022b" title="Liu J, Huang J, Zhou Y, Li X, Ji S, Xiong H, Dou D (2022b) From distributed machine learning to federated learning: a survey. Knowl Inf Syst 64(4):885–917. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s10115-022-01664-x&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR83" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e763">2022b</a>), Zhu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Zhu H, Zhang H, Jin Y (2021a) From federated learning to federated neural architecture search: a survey. Complex Intell Syst 7(2):639–657. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s40747-020-00247-z&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR193" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e766">2021a</a>) focused on the structure of FL using distributed machine learning and neural architecture. The surveys in Yu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Yu B, Mao W, Lv Y, Zhang C, Xie Y (2022) A survey on federated learning in data mining. WIREs Data Min Knowl Discov 12(1):1443. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/widm.1443&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR170" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e770">2022</a>), Zhu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Zhu H, Xu J, Liu S, Jin Y (2021b) Federated learning on non-IID data: a survey. Neurocomputing 465:371–390. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neucom.2021.07.098&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR194" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e773">2021b</a>), Jin et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Jin Y, Wei X, Liu Y, Yang Q (2020). Towards utilizing unlabeled data in federated learning: a survey and prospective. &#xA;                  arXiv:2002.11545&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR53" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e776">2020</a>), Prayitno Shyu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Prayitno Shyu C-R, Putra KT, Chen H-C, Tsai Y-Y, Hossain KSMT, Jiang W, Shae Z-Y (2021) A systematic review of federated learning in the healthcare area: from the perspective of data properties and applications. Appl Sci 11(23):11191. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.3390/app112311191&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR113" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e779">2021</a>) addressed the management of labeled data, non-IID, healthcare data, and data mining. Similarly, the surveys in Prayitno Shyu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Prayitno Shyu C-R, Putra KT, Chen H-C, Tsai Y-Y, Hossain KSMT, Jiang W, Shae Z-Y (2021) A systematic review of federated learning in the healthcare area: from the perspective of data properties and applications. Appl Sci 11(23):11191. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.3390/app112311191&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR113" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e782">2021</a>), Zheng et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Zheng Z, Zhou Y, Sun Y, Wang Z, Liu B, Li K (2022) Applications of federated learning in smart cities: recent advances, taxonomy, and open challenges. Connect Sci 34(1):1–28. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1080/09540091.2021.1936455&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR187" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e785">2022</a>), Zhou et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Zhou J, Zhang S, Lu Q, Dai W, Chen M, Liu X, Pirttikangas S, Shi Y, Zhang W, Herrera-Viedma E (2021) A survey on federated learning and its applications for accelerating industrial Internet of Things. &#xA;                  arXiv:2104.10501&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR191" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e789">2021</a>), Nguyen et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022b" title="Nguyen DC, Pham Q-V, Pathirana PN, Ding M, Seneviratne A, Lin Z, Dobre O, Hwang W-J (2022b) Federated learning for smart healthcare: a survey. ACM Comput Surv 55(3):60–16037. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3501296&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR102" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e792">2022b</a>), Antunes (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Antunes RS, André da Costa C, Küderle A, Yari IA, Eskofier B (2022) Federated learning for healthcare: systematic review and architecture proposal. ACM Trans Intell Syst Technol 13(4):54–15423. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3501813&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR6" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e795">2022</a>), Pfitzner et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Pfitzner B, Steckhan N, Arnrich B (2021) Federated learning in a medical context: a systematic literature review. ACM Trans Internet Technol 21(2):50–15031. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3412357&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR111" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e798">2021</a>), Liu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Liu M, Ho S, Wang M, Gao L, Jin Y, Zhang H (2021b) Federated learning meets natural language processing: a survey. &#xA;                  arXiv:2107.12603&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR84" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e801">2021b</a>) focused on the various applications of FL, especially in consideration to smart cities, healthcare, industrial IoT, etc. The summary above demonstrates the varied perspectives from which the surveys with respect to FL have been conducted over time.</p><p>The primary motivation of the survey presented in this work is the system model and the design of a federated Learning system. The predominant system models and design functionalities of FL have been described in this survey. In general, the most significant functionalities of the system model and design include client selection, aggregation and optimization, communication cost, knowledge transfer, data management, and incentives. These functionalities have been associated with different issues with respect to the system’s design and the development of various applications. This survey undertakes an in-depth inspection of various challenges with regards to node selection, aggregation schemes, and knowledge transfer. In this context, Sawsan Abdulrahman et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Abdulrahman S, Tout H, Ould-Slimane H, Mourad A, Talhi C, Guizani M (2021a) A survey on federated learning: the journey from centralized to distributed on-site learning and beyond. IEEE Internet Things J 8(7):5476–5497. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2020.3030072&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR1" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e807">2021a</a>) have described the classification and functionalities of the model and design of FL, as has been shown in Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Fig1">1</a>.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-1" data-title="Fig. 1"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig1" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 1</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig1_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-1-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig1_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 1" loading="lazy" width="685" height="417"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/figures/1" data-track-dest="link:Figure1 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 1" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-1-desc"><p>Functionalities and design requirements of federated learning</p></div></div></figure></div><p>In this survey, three main functionalities in terms of contributions, issues, and future directions have been addressed, more specifically: client selection, node dropping, aggregation and optimization, knowledge transfer from client to global node and global node to client node, and data management (IID and Non-IID). The client selection is a process of selecting relevant nodes to start the training using local data. The selected node then acquires the current model and waits for the next model. Node dropping is the dropping of too-slow learning nodes from the cooperative machine learning models.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-2" data-title="Fig. 2"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig2" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 2</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig2_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-2-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig2_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 2" loading="lazy" width="685" height="548"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/figures/2" data-track-dest="link:Figure2 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 2" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-2-desc"><p>Client selection process</p></div></div></figure></div><p>The aggregation and optimization model is a global node that provides an effective, high-quality model for the learning rounds. The knowledge transfer is a pre-trained model reused among the collaborative clients, with which the learning information of the clients is shared with the global node. The different characteristics and general overview of the client selection process (Nishio and Yonetani <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Nishio T, Yonetani R (2019) Client selection for federated learning with heterogeneous resources in mobile edge. In: ICC 2019—2019 IEEE international conference on communications (ICC), pp 1–7. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICC.2019.8761315&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 1938-1883" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR105" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e858">2019</a>) from registration to client selections has been demonstrated in Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Fig2">2</a>. The various steps involved in federated learning are as follows: </p><ol class="u-list-style-none">
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">i.</span>
                  
                    <p>Initialization of the participant devices.</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">ii.</span>
                  
                    <p>Request sent to the resources for participation.</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">iii.</span>
                  
                    <p>Client Selection</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">iv.</span>
                  
                    <p>Distribution of the parameters.</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">v.</span>
                  
                    <p>Updating and uploading of the new parameters, and finally.</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">vi.</span>
                  
                    <p>Aggregating the transferred weights and parameters.</p>
                  
                </li>
              </ol><p>With respect to the high requirements for the designing, collaboration, and applications of the FL system model and design, the issues that have emerged as the most pertinent for research with an eye to emerging technologies are client selection, aggregation and optimization, Knowledge transfer, and data management. In this context, the benefits and significant contributions of this paper compared to previously conducted surveys in the field can be summarized as follows: </p><ol class="u-list-style-none">
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">1.</span>
                  
                    <p>The previous surveys (Li et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020a" title="Li T, Sahu AK, Talwalkar A, Smith V (2020a) Federated learning: challenges, methods, and future directions. IEEE Signal Process Mag 37(3):50–60. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/MSP.2020.2975749&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR64" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e944">2020a</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference b" title="Li L, Fan Y, Lin K-Y (2020b) A Survey on federated learning. In: 2020 IEEE 16th international conference on control &amp; automation (ICCA), pp 791–796. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICCA51439.2020.9264412&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 1948-3457" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR73" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e947">b</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Li Q, Wen Z, Wu Z, Hu S, Wang N, Li Y, Liu X, He B (2021a) A survey on federated learning systems: vision, hype and reality for data privacy and protection. IEEE Trans Knowl Data Eng. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TKDE.2021.3124599&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR65" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e950">2021a</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022b" title="Li D, Han D, Weng T-H, Zheng Z, Li H, Liu H, Castiglione A, Li K-C (2022b) Blockchain for federated learning toward secure distributed machine learning systems: a systemic survey. Soft Comput 26(9):4423–4440. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s00500-021-06496-5&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR68" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e953">2022b</a>; Mammen <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Mammen PM (2021) Federated learning: opportunities and challenges. &#xA;                  arXiv:2101.05428&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR94" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e956">2021</a>; Abdulrahman et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Abdulrahman S, Tout H, Ould-Slimane H, Mourad A, Talhi C, Guizani M (2021a) A survey on federated learning: the journey from centralized to distributed on-site learning and beyond. IEEE Internet Things J 8(7):5476–5497. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2020.3030072&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR1" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e960">2021a</a>; Zhang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Zhang C, Xie Y, Bai H, Yu B, Li W, Gao Y (2021a) A survey on federated learning. Knowl-Based Syst 216:106775. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.knosys.2021.106775&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR176" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e963">2021a</a>; Rahman et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Rahman KMJ, Ahmed F, Akhter N, Hasan M, Amin R, Aziz KE, Islam AKMM, Mukta MSH, Islam AKMN (2021) Challenges, applications and design aspects of federated learning: a survey. IEEE Access 9:124682–124700. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ACCESS.2021.3111118&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR117" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e966">2021</a>; Xia et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Xia Q, Ye W, Tao Z, Wu J, Li Q (2021) A survey of federated learning for edge computing: Research problems and solutions. High-Confidence Comput 1(1):100008. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.hcc.2021.100008&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR154" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e969">2021</a>; Lim et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Lim WYB, Luong NC, Hoang DT, Jiao Y, Liang Y-C, Yang Q, Niyato D, Miao C (2020) Federated learning in mobile edge networks: a comprehensive survey. IEEE Commun Surv Tutor 22(3):2031–2063. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/COMST.2020.2986024&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR77" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e972">2020</a>; Nguyen et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021c" title="Nguyen DC, Ding M, Pathirana PN, Seneviratne A, Li J, Vincent Poor H (2021c) Federated learning for internet of things: a comprehensive survey. IEEE Commun Surv Tutor 23(3):1622–1658. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/COMST.2021.3075439&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR101" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e975">2021c</a>; Imteaj et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Imteaj A, Thakker U, Wang S, Li J, Amini MH (2022) A survey on federated learning for resource-constrained IoT devices. IEEE Internet Things J 9(1):1–24. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2021.3095077&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR49" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e979">2022</a>; Aledhari et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Aledhari M, Razzak R, Parizi RM, Saeed F (2020) Federated learning: a survey on enabling technologies, protocols, and applications. IEEE Access 8:140699–140725. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ACCESS.2020.3013541&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR4" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e982">2020</a>; Mothukuri et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Mothukuri V, Parizi RM, Pouriyeh S, Huang Y, Dehghantanha A, Srivastava G (2021) A survey on security and privacy of federated learning. Futur Gener Comput Syst 115:619–640. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.future.2020.10.007&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR97" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e985">2021</a>; Lyu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Lyu L, Yu H, Yang Q (2020) Threats to federated learning: a survey. &#xA;                  arXiv:2003.02133&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR91" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e988">2020</a>; Kulkarni et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Kulkarni V, Kulkarni M, Pant, A (2020) Survey of personalization techniques for federated learning. In: 2020 fourth world conference on smart trends in systems, security and sustainability (WorldS4), pp 794–797. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/WorldS450073.2020.9210355&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR59" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e991">2020</a>; Blanco-Justicia et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Blanco-Justicia A, Domingo-Ferrer J, Martínez S, Sánchez D, Flanagan A, Tan KE (2021) Achieving security and privacy in federated learning systems: survey, research challenges and future directions. Eng Appl Artif Intell 106:104468. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.engappai.2021.104468&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR9" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e994">2021</a>; Ghimire and Rawat <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Ghimire B, Rawat DB (2022) Recent advances on federated learning for cybersecurity and cybersecurity for federated learning for Internet of Things. IEEE Internet Things J 9(11):8229–8249. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2022.3150363&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR33" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e998">2022</a>; Yin et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Yin X, Zhu Y, Hu J (2021) A comprehensive survey of privacy-preserving federated learning: a taxonomy, review, and future directions. ACM Comput Surv 54(6):131–113136. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3460427&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR168" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1001">2021</a>; Ouadrhiri and Abdelhadi <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Ouadrhiri AE, Abdelhadi A (2022) Differential privacy for deep and federated learning: a survey. IEEE Access 10:22359–22380. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ACCESS.2022.3151670&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR107" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1004">2022</a>; Kholod et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Kholod I, Yanaki E, Fomichev D, Shalugin E, Novikova E, Filippov E, Nordlund M (2020) Open-source federated learning frameworks for IoT: a comparative review and analysis. Sensors 21(1):167. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.3390/s21010167&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR55" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1007">2020</a>; Liu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Liu M, Ho S, Wang M, Gao L, Jin Y, Zhang H (2021b) Federated learning meets natural language processing: a survey. &#xA;                  arXiv:2107.12603&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR84" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1010">2021b</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022b" title="Liu J, Huang J, Zhou Y, Li X, Ji S, Xiong H, Dou D (2022b) From distributed machine learning to federated learning: a survey. Knowl Inf Syst 64(4):885–917. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s10115-022-01664-x&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR83" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1013">2022b</a>; Zhu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Zhu H, Zhang H, Jin Y (2021a) From federated learning to federated neural architecture search: a survey. Complex Intell Syst 7(2):639–657. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s40747-020-00247-z&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR193" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1017">2021a</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference b" title="Zhu H, Xu J, Liu S, Jin Y (2021b) Federated learning on non-IID data: a survey. Neurocomputing 465:371–390. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neucom.2021.07.098&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR194" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1020">b</a>; Yu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Yu B, Mao W, Lv Y, Zhang C, Xie Y (2022) A survey on federated learning in data mining. WIREs Data Min Knowl Discov 12(1):1443. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/widm.1443&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR170" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1023">2022</a>; Jin et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Jin Y, Wei X, Liu Y, Yang Q (2020). Towards utilizing unlabeled data in federated learning: a survey and prospective. &#xA;                  arXiv:2002.11545&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR53" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1026">2020</a>; Prayitno Shyu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Prayitno Shyu C-R, Putra KT, Chen H-C, Tsai Y-Y, Hossain KSMT, Jiang W, Shae Z-Y (2021) A systematic review of federated learning in the healthcare area: from the perspective of data properties and applications. Appl Sci 11(23):11191. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.3390/app112311191&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR113" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1029">2021</a>; Zheng et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Zheng Z, Zhou Y, Sun Y, Wang Z, Liu B, Li K (2022) Applications of federated learning in smart cities: recent advances, taxonomy, and open challenges. Connect Sci 34(1):1–28. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1080/09540091.2021.1936455&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR187" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1032">2022</a>; Zhou et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Zhou J, Zhang S, Lu Q, Dai W, Chen M, Liu X, Pirttikangas S, Shi Y, Zhang W, Herrera-Viedma E (2021) A survey on federated learning and its applications for accelerating industrial Internet of Things. &#xA;                  arXiv:2104.10501&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR191" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1036">2021</a>; Nguyen et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022b" title="Nguyen DC, Pham Q-V, Pathirana PN, Ding M, Seneviratne A, Lin Z, Dobre O, Hwang W-J (2022b) Federated learning for smart healthcare: a survey. ACM Comput Surv 55(3):60–16037. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3501296&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR102" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1039">2022b</a>; Antunes <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Antunes RS, André da Costa C, Küderle A, Yari IA, Eskofier B (2022) Federated learning for healthcare: systematic review and architecture proposal. ACM Trans Intell Syst Technol 13(4):54–15423. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3501813&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR6" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1042">2022</a>; Pfitzner et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Pfitzner B, Steckhan N, Arnrich B (2021) Federated learning in a medical context: a systematic literature review. ACM Trans Internet Technol 21(2):50–15031. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3412357&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR111" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1045">2021</a>) have mostly described FL challenges and opportunities, open-source frameworks, privacy, as well as different applications and emergent technologies such as edge computing and IoT. In contrast, this survey focuses specifically on the FL system model and design and the corresponding issues related to the various functionalities of the FL model and design.</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">2.</span>
                  
                    <p>Further elaboration is made on functionalities such as different client/node selection, and dropping node approaches with respect to various objectives, parameters, and characteristics are briefly described and compared.</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">3.</span>
                  
                    <p>In-depth analysis is provided of different aggregation and optimization methods in terms of various parameters and knowledge transfer from aggregation methods to client briefly discussed.</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">4.</span>
                  
                    <p>The different approaches to knowledge transfer methods, client data management, and cost management methods are analyzed and briefly described.</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">5.</span>
                  
                    <p>Finally how federated learning functionalities are used in different applications and the future direction of the research in terms of designing effective federated learning are presented.</p>
                  
                </li>
              </ol><p>The rest of the work has been presented as follows. Section <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="section anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Sec2">2</a> compares and examines node selection and node dropping methods. Section <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="section anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Sec3">3</a> provides a comparative analysis of the various aggregation and optimization methods. Section <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="section anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Sec4">4</a> provides elaboration on knowledge transfer methods, and Sect. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="section anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Sec5">5</a> describes data management on the client side. Section <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="section anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Sec6">6</a> presented Incentive management methods, and Sect. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="section anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Sec7">7</a> described communication Cost reduce Methods. Section <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="section anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Sec8">8</a> presents how federated learning is applied to various applications. Finally, Sect. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="section anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Sec9">9</a> provides a summary of issues and directions for future research related to the design of effective methods in federated learning, and Sect. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="section anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Sec10">10</a> provides the conclusion.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Node selection and dropping methods"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec2-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec2"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">2 </span>Node selection and dropping methods</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec2-content"><p><b>Node Selection Methods</b> Client selection is a typical process in Federated learning where initially the device in question is charged and idle. All the registered edge devices are connected and associated to the server or global node to receive the global model and to transfer the communication accuracy and collected features and weights. The different characteristics and general overview of the client selection process (Nishio and Yonetani <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Nishio T, Yonetani R (2019) Client selection for federated learning with heterogeneous resources in mobile edge. In: ICC 2019—2019 IEEE international conference on communications (ICC), pp 1–7. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICC.2019.8761315&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 1938-1883" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR105" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1135">2019</a>) from registration to client selections has been demonstrated in Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Fig3">3</a>.</p><p>In this section that elaborates upon the client selection process, different client selection methods and related feedback have been summarized. The different client selection methods have been presented in the references (Nishio and Yonetani <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Nishio T, Yonetani R (2019) Client selection for federated learning with heterogeneous resources in mobile edge. In: ICC 2019—2019 IEEE international conference on communications (ICC), pp 1–7. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICC.2019.8761315&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 1938-1883" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR105" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1144">2019</a>; Yoshida et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Yoshida N, Nishio T, Morikura M, Yamamoto K (2020) MAB-based client selection for federated learning with uncertain resources in mobile networks. In: 2020 IEEE Globecom workshops, GC Wkshps, pp 1–6. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/GCWkshps50303.2020.9367421&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR169" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1147">2020</a>; Li et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022g" title="Li C, Zeng X, Zhang M, Cao Z (2022g) PyramidFL: a fine-grained client selection framework for efficient federated learning. In: Proceedings of ACM MobiCom, Sydney, p 14" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR86" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1150">2022g</a>; Tang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Tang M, Ning X, Wang Y, Sun J, Wang Y, Li H, Chen Y (2022) FedCor: correlation-based active client selection strategy for heterogeneous federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:2103.13822&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR135" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1153">2022</a>; Che et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Che C, Li X, Chen C, He X, Zheng Z (2021) A decentralized federated learning framework via committee mechanism with convergence guarantee. &#xA;                  arXiv:2108.00365&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR13" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1156">2021</a>; Xu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022b" title="Xu J, Chen Z, Quek TQS, Chong KFE (2022b) FedCorr: multi-stage federated learning for label noise correction. &#xA;                  arXiv:2204.04677&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR159" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1160">2022b</a>; Zhao and Joshi <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Zhao Z, Joshi G (2022) A dynamic reweighting strategy for fair federated learning. In: ICASSP 2022 - 2022 IEEE international conference on acoustics, speech and signal processing (ICASSP), pp 8772–8776. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICASSP43922.2022.9746300&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2379-190X" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR186" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1163">2022</a>; Cho et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Cho YJ, Wang J, Joshi G (2020) Client selection in federated learning: convergence analysis and power-of-choice selection strategies. &#xA;                  arXiv:2010.01243&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR24" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1166">2020</a>; Larsson et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Larsson H, Riaz H, Ickin S (2021) Automated collaborator selection for federated learning with multi-armed bandit agents. In: Proceedings of the 4th FlexNets workshop on flexible networks artificial intelligence supported network flexibility and agility. FlexNets ’21. Association for Computing Machinery, New York, NY, USA, pp 44–49. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3472735.3473388&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR61" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1169">2021</a>; Hosseinzadeh et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Hosseinzadeh M, Hudson N, Heshmati S, Khamfroush H (2022) Communication-loss trade-off in federated learning: a distributed client selection algorithm. In: 2022 IEEE 19th annual consumer communications &amp; networking conference (CCNC), pp 1–6. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/CCNC49033.2022.9700601&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2331-9860" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR44" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1172">2022</a>; Wang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Wang J, Xu Z, Garrett Z, Charles Z, Liu L, Joshi G (2021b) Local adaptivity in federated learning: convergence and consistency. &#xA;                  arXiv:2106.02305&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR146" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1175">2021b</a>; Luo et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Luo B, Xiao W, Wang S, Huang J, Tassiulas L (2021b) Tackling system and statistical heterogeneity for federated learning with adaptive client sampling. &#xA;                  arXiv:2112.11256&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR90" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1179">2021b</a>; Zheng et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Zheng J, Li K, Tovar E, Guizani M (2021) Federated learning for energy-balanced client selection in mobile edge computing. In: 2021 international wireless communications and mobile computing (IWCMC), pp 1942–1947. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/IWCMC51323.2021.9498853&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2376-6506" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR188" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1182">2021</a>; Tang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Tang M, Ning X, Wang Y, Wang Y, Chen Y (2021) FedGP: correlation-based active client selection for heterogeneous federated learning. &#xA;                  https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/FedGP&#xA;                  &#xA;                 Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR136" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1185">2021</a>; Cha et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Cha N, Du Z, Wu C, Yoshinaga T, Zhong L, Ma J, Liu F, Ji Y (2022) Fuzzy logic based client selection for federated learning in vehicular networks. IEEE Open J Comput Soc 3:39–50. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/OJCS.2022.3163620&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR11" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1188">2022</a>; Wu and Wang <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Wu H, Wang P (2022) Node selection toward faster convergence for federated learning on non-IID data. IEEE Trans Netw Sci Eng. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TNSE.2022.3146399&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR149" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1191">2022</a>; Xu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Xu B, Xia W, Zhang J, Quek TQS, Zhu H (2021b) Online client scheduling for fast federated learning. IEEE Wirel Commun Lett 10(7):1434–1438. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/LWC.2021.3069541&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR157" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1194">2021b</a>; Lai et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Lai F, Zhu X, Madhyastha HV, Chowdhury M (2021) Oort: efficient federated learning via guided participant selection, pp 19–35. &#xA;                  https://www.usenix.org/conference/osdi21/presentation/lai&#xA;                  &#xA;                 Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR60" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1198">2021</a>; Huang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Huang T, Lin W, Shen L, Li K, Zomaya AY (2022) Stochastic client selection for federated learning with volatile clients. IEEE Internet Things J. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2022.3172113&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR47" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1201">2022</a>; Abdulrahman et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Abdulrahman S, Tout H, Mourad A, Talhi C (2021b) FedMCCS: multicriteria client selection model for optimal IoT federated learning. IEEE Internet Things J 8(6):4723–4735. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2020.3028742&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR2" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1204">2021b</a>; Rai et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Rai S, Kumari A, Prasad DK (2022) Client selection in federated learning under imperfections in environment. AI 3(1):124–145" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR118" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1207">2022</a>; Malandrino and Chiasserini <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Malandrino F, Chiasserini CF (2021) Federated learning at the network edge: when not all nodes are created equal. IEEE Commun Mag 59(7):68–73. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/MCOM.001.2001016&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR93" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1210">2021</a>; Shin et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Shin M, Hwang C, Kim J, Park J, Bennis M, Kim S-L (2020) XOR Mixup: privacy-preserving data augmentation for one-shot federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:2006.05148&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR131" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1213">2020</a>) while the different goals, datasets for the implementation and the metrics for the evaluation have been summarized in Table <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Tab2">2</a>. In this case, the FedCS (Nishio and Yonetani <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Nishio T, Yonetani R (2019) Client selection for federated learning with heterogeneous resources in mobile edge. In: ICC 2019—2019 IEEE international conference on communications (ICC), pp 1–7. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICC.2019.8761315&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 1938-1883" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR105" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1220">2019</a>) was chosen as the primary client selection method and the main goal of this method is to actively select the client based on the resource condition. The selection was performed using random criteria and the main drawback of this work was not considering dynamic scenarios and fluctuating dynamic updating. To address this, the multi-armed bandit (Yoshida et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Yoshida N, Nishio T, Morikura M, Yamamoto K (2020) MAB-based client selection for federated learning with uncertain resources in mobile networks. In: 2020 IEEE Globecom workshops, GC Wkshps, pp 1–6. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/GCWkshps50303.2020.9367421&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR169" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1223">2020</a>) method was used to reduce the exploration and the exploitation and trade off in the mobile network. This method helps manage uncertainty caused by a huge amount of data, and one of the main advantages of this method is the reduction in learning time and is recommended in future scenarios for reducing resource usage in fluctuating FL operations.</p><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-2"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab2" data-test="table-caption">Table 2 Summary of client selection methods</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/tables/2" aria-label="Full size table 2"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-3" data-title="Fig. 3"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig3" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 3</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig3_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-3-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig3_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 3" loading="lazy" width="685" height="745"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/figures/3" data-track-dest="link:Figure3 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 3" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-3-desc"><p>Client selection process</p></div></div></figure></div><p>The Power-of-Choice (Cho et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Cho YJ, Wang J, Joshi G (2020) Client selection in federated learning: convergence analysis and power-of-choice selection strategies. &#xA;                  arXiv:2010.01243&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR24" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1857">2020</a>) model provides the guarantee of federated learning while managing communication, computational limitations as well as the heterogeneous data. In this method, the client selection is performed based on the random selection criteria. Additionally, the Power-of-Choice (Xu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022b" title="Xu J, Chen Z, Quek TQS, Chong KFE (2022b) FedCorr: multi-stage federated learning for label noise correction. &#xA;                  arXiv:2204.04677&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR159" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1860">2022b</a>) method has been used for managing biased client selection and has received better convergence rates compared to the random client selection method. Better performance in terms of faster convergence and more consistent management is made possible using methods like arbitrary client selection (Wang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Wang J, Xu Z, Garrett Z, Charles Z, Liu L, Joshi G (2021b) Local adaptivity in federated learning: convergence and consistency. &#xA;                  arXiv:2106.02305&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR146" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1863">2021b</a>) and adaptive client selection (Luo et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Luo B, Xiao W, Wang S, Huang J, Tassiulas L (2021b) Tackling system and statistical heterogeneity for federated learning with adaptive client sampling. &#xA;                  arXiv:2112.11256&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR90" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1866">2021b</a>) by assessing and updating probabilities pertaining to the client relationships. Using these types of client selection can help manage unknown parameters used for solving complex problems. Another approach based on client selection trade-off, where energy consumption is reduced with the help of a heuristic-based method is called FedAECS (Zheng et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Zheng J, Li K, Tovar E, Guizani M (2021) Federated learning for energy-balanced client selection in mobile edge computing. In: 2021 international wireless communications and mobile computing (IWCMC), pp 1942–1947. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/IWCMC51323.2021.9498853&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2376-6506" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR188" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1869">2021</a>). Similarly, the correlation-based Gaussian process (FedGP) (Tang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Tang M, Ning X, Wang Y, Wang Y, Chen Y (2021) FedGP: correlation-based active client selection for heterogeneous federated learning. &#xA;                  https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/FedGP&#xA;                  &#xA;                 Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR136" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1873">2021</a>) and the correlation-based client selection process (Fedcor) (Tang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Tang M, Ning X, Wang Y, Sun J, Wang Y, Li H, Chen Y (2022) FedCor: correlation-based active client selection strategy for heterogeneous federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:2103.13822&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR135" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1876">2022</a>) used for the management of heterogeneous help to reduce communication overheads and communication costs. The CMFL Che et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Che C, Li X, Chen C, He X, Zheng Z (2021) A decentralized federated learning framework via committee mechanism with convergence guarantee. &#xA;                  arXiv:2108.00365&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR13" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1879">2021</a>) framework, on the other hand, used for random selection, in which two different selection strategies are used for managing the robustness and convergence of the selection strategies, results in faster convergence and better selection performance. The automated collaborator selection strategy for the management of non-iid data performed using multi armed bandit (MAB) (Yoshida et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Yoshida N, Nishio T, Morikura M, Yamamoto K (2020) MAB-based client selection for federated learning with uncertain resources in mobile networks. In: 2020 IEEE Globecom workshops, GC Wkshps, pp 1–6. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/GCWkshps50303.2020.9367421&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR169" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1882">2020</a>) method has also been used to manage the overall benefits of federated selection.</p><p>Another improved federated training approach based on fine grained selection (Li et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022g" title="Li C, Zeng X, Zhang M, Cao Z (2022g) PyramidFL: a fine-grained client selection framework for efficient federated learning. In: Proceedings of ACM MobiCom, Sydney, p 14" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR86" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1888">2022g</a>) is called the pyramidFL framework and has been used to improve the time-to-accuracy performance of federated learning. With the help of this framework, the local data efficiency is seen to improve, and the communication cost is reduced, while overall improving end-to-end performance. Another framework, the Fedcorr (Xu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022b" title="Xu J, Chen Z, Quek TQS, Chong KFE (2022b) FedCorr: multi-stage federated learning for label noise correction. &#xA;                  arXiv:2204.04677&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR159" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1891">2022b</a>) multi-stage selection framework, used for managing noise of local clients while independently managing all the clients, has been noted for increasing the fairness of the federated learning process by adjusting the client selection strategies and overall improving the efficiency of the results. The DRFL (Zhao and Joshi <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Zhao Z, Joshi G (2022) A dynamic reweighting strategy for fair federated learning. In: ICASSP 2022 - 2022 IEEE international conference on acoustics, speech and signal processing (ICASSP), pp 8772–8776. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICASSP43922.2022.9746300&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2379-190X" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR186" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1894">2022</a>) method is used to improve the weight accorded to each client and thereby increase the fairness of the result. In distributed client selections, it is an inherent challenge to address the problem arising out of the the trade-off between communication and cost.</p><p>The Distributed Client Selection (DCS) (Hosseinzadeh et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Hosseinzadeh M, Hudson N, Heshmati S, Khamfroush H (2022) Communication-loss trade-off in federated learning: a distributed client selection algorithm. In: 2022 IEEE 19th annual consumer communications &amp; networking conference (CCNC), pp 1–6. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/CCNC49033.2022.9700601&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2331-9860" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR44" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1900">2022</a>) method is used to alleviate this problem and using this, about 32.67% of the overall cost is seen to be reduced. In another approach, a fuzzy logic (Cha et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Cha N, Du Z, Wu C, Yoshinaga T, Zhong L, Ma J, Liu F, Ji Y (2022) Fuzzy logic based client selection for federated learning in vehicular networks. IEEE Open J Comput Soc 3:39–50. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/OJCS.2022.3163620&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR11" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1903">2022</a>) based client selection method has been used in vehicular networks for managing heterogeneous data and network throughput. In this fuzzy logic-based client selection, multiple factors including network throughput is used for client selection. For achieving faster convergence of non-iid data, FedPNS (Wu and Wang <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Wu H, Wang P (2022) Node selection toward faster convergence for federated learning on non-IID data. IEEE Trans Netw Sci Eng. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TNSE.2022.3146399&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR149" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1906">2022</a>) node selection has been used, where the selection probability of each node is changed dynamically depending on the optimal aggregation. In another scenario, the MAB method (Xu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Xu B, Xia W, Zhang J, Quek TQS, Zhu H (2021b) Online client scheduling for fast federated learning. IEEE Wirel Commun Lett 10(7):1434–1438. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/LWC.2021.3069541&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR157" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1909">2021b</a>) has been used with a greedy algorithm to achieve trade-offs that may enhance suitability for optimization. This method has been observed to minimize communication delays, thus reducing training latency. In order to circumvent the poor system efficiency usually associated with random client selection, researchers have introduced a guided participant selection method called Oort (Lai et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Lai F, Zhu X, Madhyastha HV, Chowdhury M (2021) Oort: efficient federated learning via guided participant selection, pp 19–35. &#xA;                  https://www.usenix.org/conference/osdi21/presentation/lai&#xA;                  &#xA;                 Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR60" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1912">2021</a>).</p><p>Another method for avoiding random selection is the multi-criteria approach that is used for selecting the client in FL. Using this method, the number of communication rounds is reduced, while maximizing the number of clients and reducing the number of discarded client sessions at the same time. Use of this model has led to improvements in model accuracy and has helped train clients quickly. Volatile client selection methods have led to reduced performance in a Federated Learning system, affecting the training efficiency as well as fairness. To avoid this problem, a stochastic client selection (E3CS) scheme (Huang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Huang T, Lin W, Shen L, Li K, Zomaya AY (2022) Stochastic client selection for federated learning with volatile clients. IEEE Internet Things J. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2022.3172113&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR47" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1918">2022</a>) has been used, which has resulted in a fixed accuracy as well as faster convergence. In scenarios with imperfect data, an irrelevance sampling method has been proposed for client selection (Rai et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Rai S, Kumari A, Prasad DK (2022) Client selection in federated learning under imperfections in environment. AI 3(1):124–145" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR118" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1921">2022</a>), which generates an irrelevance score that considers the client characteristics. This method has resulted in faster convergence as well.</p><p>In the distributed large-scale neural network used, multiple edge nodes were used for local updates. To manage this scenario, a secure node selection method based on a blockchain-based random client selection method was introduced. Using this method resulted in improved privacy (Qammar et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2023" title="Qammar A, Naouri A, Ding J, Ning H (2023) Blockchain-based optimized edge node selection and privacy preserved framework for federated learning. Clust Comput 1–16" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR114" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1927">2023</a>; Li et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020a" title="Li T, Sahu AK, Talwalkar A, Smith V (2020a) Federated learning: challenges, methods, and future directions. IEEE Signal Process Mag 37(3):50–60. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/MSP.2020.2975749&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR64" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1930">2020a</a>). similarly, in a distributed IoT device selection, a resource-constrained based node selection method called the DDQN-trust solution uses random selection techniques. This DDQN method was integrated with various federated averaging methods such as FedAvg, FedProx and FedSGD (Rjoub et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2024" title="Rjoub G, Wahab OA, Bentahar J, Bataineh A (2024) Trust-driven reinforcement selection strategy for federated learning on iot devices. Computing 106(4):1273–1295" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR124" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1933">2024</a>). Another technique, deep reinforcement learning method-based node selection, was introduced for heterogeneous data in a distributed client selection. This client selection was performed based on the client quality record for a dynamic environment using the Markov decision process and CS-A2C (Li et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2024" title="Li Z, Dang Y, Chen X (2024) Node selection for model quality optimization in hierarchical federated learning based on deep reinforcement learning. Peer-to-Peer Netw Appl 1–12" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR71" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1936">2024</a>). For edge computing in the IoT environment, the deep reinforcement learning-based node selection was introduced, and heterogeneous data was utilized in the edge devices. Using this method, better privacy was achieved (Yan et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2023" title="Yan S, Zhang P, Huang S, Wang J, Sun H, Zhang Y, Tolba A (2023) Node selection algorithm for federated learning based on deep reinforcement learning for edge computing in iot. Electronics 12(11):2478" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR160" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e1939">2023</a>). The grouped similar techniques based on the selection strategies such as random, resource constraints, bandwidth, etc presented in Table <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Tab3">3</a>.</p><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-3"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab3" data-test="table-caption">Table 3 Summary of similar techniques based on the selection strategies</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/tables/3" aria-label="Full size table 3"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><p><b>Dropping of Nodes</b> Node dropping refers to the temporary or permanent removal of certain clients from training rounds. This can occur for multiple reasons, such as limited resources, network instability, and strategies adopted to improve efficiency and scalability. The main task of Federated Learning is cooperatively training the machine learning model using a central server to coordinate with multiple participants or clients. These servers may occasionally drop slow nodes from the learning process. The authors of Malandrino and Chiasserini (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Malandrino F, Chiasserini CF (2021) Federated learning at the network edge: when not all nodes are created equal. IEEE Commun Mag 59(7):68–73. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/MCOM.001.2001016&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR93" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2148">2021</a>) suggested some key issues that may lead to the dropping of nodes from the learning process as follows: </p><ol class="u-list-style-none">
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">i.</span>
                  
                    <p>Insufficient quality of data.</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">ii.</span>
                  
                    <p>Slow learning.</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">iii.</span>
                  
                    <p>Low bandwidth.</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">iv.</span>
                  
                    <p>lack of updates and a high degree of noise.</p>
                  
                </li>
              </ol><p>Some other reasons that may be considered before dropping nodes are Non-homogeneous client data and Node with different capabilities. The authors of Wang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2023" title="Wang L, Zhao X, Lu Z, Wang L, Zhang S (2023) Enhancing privacy preservation and trustworthiness for decentralized federated learning. Inf Sci 628:449–468" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR141" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2198">2023</a>) and Li et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022c" title="Li Y, Li H, Xu G, Xiang T, Lu R (2022c) Practical privacy-preserving federated learning in vehicular fog computing. IEEE Trans Veh Technol 71(5):4692–4705" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR69" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2201">2022c</a>) used node drop strategies for data privacy in a decentralized federated learning system. Wang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2023" title="Wang L, Zhao X, Lu Z, Wang L, Zhang S (2023) Enhancing privacy preservation and trustworthiness for decentralized federated learning. Inf Sci 628:449–468" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR141" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2204">2023</a>), used zk-SNARK techniques to enhance the trustworthiness of the node, using node dropping and joining strategies. Similarly, Li et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022c" title="Li Y, Li H, Xu G, Xiang T, Lu R (2022c) Practical privacy-preserving federated learning in vehicular fog computing. IEEE Trans Veh Technol 71(5):4692–4705" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR69" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2208">2022c</a>), proposed a framework called GALAXY to achieve privacy in a cooperative multiple-user framework, permitting a certain number of fog nodes to cooperate and keeping the system robust with a certain number of fog nodes dropping out simultaneously. Using this GALAXY framework led to better scalability, higher efficiency, and reduced resource overheads in fog environments. For the large classes of clients, FL-FDMS was introduced in the distributed environment for data similarity. In this FL-FDMS, the clients are dropped out of the distributed environments (Wang and Xu <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Wang H, Xu J (2022) Combating client dropout in federated learning via friend model substitution. arXiv preprint &#xA;                  arXiv:2205.13222&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR145" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2211">2022</a>) using the similarity of data.</p><p><b>Implications and Robustness of node dropping</b> There are various positive and negative implications of the learning process in federated learning. Reducing communication costs and overheads, proper resource utilization, better model convergence, coordination of clients, fault tolerance, managing attacks from the suspected nodes, and adaptive learning from the relevant and effective resources are some of the positive implications and areas of robustness. Data representation loss from unique and important clients, potential bias due to certain types of clients, reduced diversity due to a less diverse training dataset, and dependency on only high-performance clients to significantly reduce the training process of FL are some of the negative implications of node dropping.</p><p><b>Discussion</b> Most of the client selection methods employed till date have been based on random selection, resource constraint selection, and bandwidth-based client selection patterns as a means of selecting clients. These types of client selection patterns typically give rise to issues such as increased communication costs, inadequate quality of data and lack of effective clients since in such selection methods, frequent updating of data is not given due consideration.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Aggregation methods"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec3-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec3"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">3 </span>Aggregation methods</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec3-content"><p>The main goal of FL is generating an effective global model with the help of models learned on the distributed local data of the participating clients. The high quality of data of the learned client models are then aggregated or combined to generate a new kind of model called the aggregation model. In general, both aggregation algorithms and rank aggregation algorithms are applied with different application such as internet applications, meta-data analysis, etc. The algorithms generally used for the aggregation (Lin <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2010" title="Lin S (2010) Rank aggregation methods. WIREs Comput Stat 2(5):555–570. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1002/wics.111&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR78" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2232">2010</a>) are mainly heuristic and stochastic in nature. There are usually two layers of aggregation incorporated in federated learning, such as local device aggregation and federated or cross device aggregation (McMahan et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2017" title="McMahan B, Moore E, Ramage D, Hampson S, Arcas BAy (2017) Communication-efficient learning of deep networks from decentralized data. In: Proceedings of the 20th international conference on artificial intelligence and statistics, pp 1273–1282. PMLR. ISSN: 2640-3498. &#xA;                  https://proceedings.mlr.press/v54/mcmahan17a.html&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 11 May 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR95" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2235">2017</a>).</p><p><b>Local Aggregation</b> Local aggregation refers to the multiple samples owned by individual clients. It uses the model parameters while sequentially using the local parameters as well. It considers computer accuracy, average loss, and other metrics for local iterations with the help of local streams Federated Learning | TensorFlow Federated. <a href="https://www.tensorflow.org/federated/federated_learning">https://www.tensorflow.org/federated/federated_learning</a>.</p><p><b>Federated Aggregation</b> Federated aggregation is also referred to as cross-device aggregation. This refers to aggregation across multiple connected devices and uses model parameters, averaged client aggregations as well as other metrics from the model in order to arrive at a global model Federated Learning | TensorFlow Federated. <a href="https://www.tensorflow.org/federated/federated_learning">https://www.tensorflow.org/federated/federated_learning</a>. The diagrammatic representation of a Federated Aggregation structure is illustrated in Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Fig4">4</a>. Researchers in the area have considered different federated aggregation methods over time to arrive at effective models.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-4" data-title="Fig. 4"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig4" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 4</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig4_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-4-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig4_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 4" loading="lazy" width="685" height="594"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/figures/4" data-track-dest="link:Figure4 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 4" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-4-desc"><p>Federated aggregation structure</p></div></div></figure></div><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-4"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab4" data-test="table-caption">Table 4 Summary of aggregation methods</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/tables/4" aria-label="Full size table 4"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><p>Initially, federated averaging Yao et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Yao X, Huang T, Zhang R-X, Li R, Sun L (2020) Federated learning with unbiased gradient aggregation and controllable meta updating. &#xA;                  arXiv:1910.08234&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR165" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2864">2020</a>) was introduced using a stochastic gradient optimization for averaging five different models using four datasets. This was the base model for federated aggregation. Konečný et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2016" title="Konečný J, McMahan HB, Ramage D, Richtárik P (2016) Federated optimization: distributed machine learning for on-device intelligence. &#xA;                  arXiv:1610.02527&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR56" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2867">2016</a>) subsequently introduced unevenly distributed large nodes for training the centralized model using high quality data. This process was called “federated optimization” or “algorithm.” In this method, features, number of nodes, and communication rounds were used for evaluation. Continuing the thread, Wang (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2017" title="Wang Y (2017) CO-OP: cooperative machine learning from mobile devices. Master’s thesis, University of Alberta. Publisher: University of Alberta Libraries. &#xA;                  https://era.library.ualberta.ca/items/7d680f04-7987-45c5-b9cd-4fe43c87606f&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR138" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2870">2017</a>) conducted further research and proposed an asynchronous protocol called CO-OP for training the local model with the help of newly generated samples and merging the local samples into global models. In this work, model accuracy and communication overhead parameters were considered for evaluation.</p><p>These references (Konečný et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2016" title="Konečný J, McMahan HB, Ramage D, Richtárik P (2016) Federated optimization: distributed machine learning for on-device intelligence. &#xA;                  arXiv:1610.02527&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR56" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2876">2016</a>; Wang <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2017" title="Wang Y (2017) CO-OP: cooperative machine learning from mobile devices. Master’s thesis, University of Alberta. Publisher: University of Alberta Libraries. &#xA;                  https://era.library.ualberta.ca/items/7d680f04-7987-45c5-b9cd-4fe43c87606f&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR138" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2879">2017</a>; Guha et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Guha N, Talwalkar A, Smith V (2019) One-shot federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:1902.11175&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR34" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2882">2019</a>) point to the base aggregation models, based on which future models were developed. Using the one-shot federated learning (Guha et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Guha N, Talwalkar A, Smith V (2019) One-shot federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:1902.11175&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR34" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2885">2019</a>) method, the entire participant devices’ knowledge was shared within a single round of communication. But the average relative gain was found to be only 51.5%. The periodic average (Haddadpour and Mahdavi <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Haddadpour F, Mahdavi M (2019) On the convergence of local descent methods in federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:1910.14425&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR36" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2888">2019</a>) was calculated using different data distributions, the unbiased gradient and sample schema, and the polyak-lojasiewkz condition, which provided the best convergence rates. To manage corrupted updates, a robust aggregation method (Pillutla et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Pillutla K, Kakade SM, Harchaoui Z (2022) Robust aggregation for federated learning. IEEE Trans Signal Process 70:1142–1154. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TSP.2022.3153135&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR112" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2892">2022</a>) was used with the help of a geometric median (GM). The author, Xie et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Xie M, Long G, Shen T, Zhou T, Wang X, Jiang J, Zhang C (2021) Multi-center federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:2005.01026&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR155" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2895">2021</a>), presented a discrepancy in the data distribution, and proposed a multi-center federated aggregation using different global nodes. To avoid end-to-end training latency, the author of Jiang and Hu (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Jiang J, Hu L (2020) Decentralised federated learning with adaptive partial gradient aggregation. CAAI Trans Intell Technol 5(3):230–236. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1049/trit.2020.0082&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR51" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2898">2020</a>) proposed the FedPGA mechanism to exchange the particle gradient mechanism and to speed up the overall communication process and to reduce communication overheads. Time and accuracy were the two evaluation parameters that were considered in the evaluation. The IDA (Yeganeh et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Yeganeh Y, Farshad A, Navab N, Albarqouni S (2020) Inverse distance aggregation for federated learning with non-IID data. In: Albarqouni S, Bakas S, Kamnitsas K, Cardoso MJ, Landman B, Li W, Milletari F, Rieke N, Roth H, Xu D, Xu Z (eds) Domain adaptation and representation transfer, and distributed and collaborative learning. Lecture Notes in Computer Science. Springer, Cham, pp 150–159. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-60548-3_15&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR166" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2901">2020</a>) aggregation method was used to robustly aggregate clients using the parameters and the FEDBE (Chen and Chao <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Chen H-Y, Chao W-L (2021) FedBE: making bayesian model ensemble applicable to federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:2009.01974&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR14" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2904">2021</a>) model was used to robustly aggregate the performance using a Bayesian ensemble model. This model was used to send single round trains to the clients and multiple rounds were avoided.</p><p>To avoid the scenario of different clients having different local models, a model called MHAT (Hu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Hu L, Yan H, Li L, Pan Z, Liu X, Zhang Z (2021) MHAT: an efficient model-heterogenous aggregation training scheme for federated learning. Inf Sci 560:493–503. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ins.2021.01.046&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR46" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2910">2021</a>) was proposed to make an auxiliary model to extract and update the real information for aggregation and reduce the communication rounds. The author of Wang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Wang H, Yurochkin M, Sun Y, Papailiopoulos D, Khazaeni Y (2020) Federated learning with matched averaging. &#xA;                  arXiv:2002.06440&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR147" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2913">2020</a>) introduced a matched average aggregation method using hidden elements such as the hidden layers of the CNN and LSTM algorithms and connected layers-wise matching was then performed. Using this method, the communication overhead and rounds were reduced. To avoid unnecessary server updates and scalability issues, the authors of Nguyen et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022d" title="Nguyen J, Malik K, Zhan H, Yousefpour A, Rabbat M, Malek M, Huba D (2022d) Federated learning with buffered asynchronous aggregation. In: Proceedings of The 25th international conference on artificial intelligence and statistics, pp 3581–3607. PMLR. ISSN: 2640-3498. &#xA;                  https://proceedings.mlr.press/v151/nguyen22b.html&#xA;                  &#xA;                 Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR104" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2916">2022d</a>) proposed a model called FedBuff. In this model, before updates to the server were made, ‘K’ client updates were stored in a sequential buffer, before being updated to the server. To increase fairness and robustness, the authors proposed a model called Ditto (Li et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021c" title="Li T, Hu S, Beirami A, Smith V (2021c) Ditto: fair and robust federated learning through personalization. In: Proceedings of the 38th international conference on machine learning, pp 6357–6368. PMLR. ISSN: 2640-3498. &#xA;                  https://proceedings.mlr.press/v139/li21h.html&#xA;                  &#xA;                 Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR75" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2919">2021c</a>).</p><p>In this framework, a single framework for multi-tasking learning was performed. In this work, two tasks, such as global and local model objectives, were used to incorporate and regulate the optimal global model. The authors of Elkordy and Avestimehr (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Elkordy AR, Avestimehr AS (2021) Secure aggregation with heterogeneous quantization in federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:2009.14388&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR29" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2925">2021</a>) provide a method for sequential aggregation using heterogeneous quantization. Using this method, edge users adjusted the quantization to the resources available and succeeded in providing better accuracy and lower communication costs. In another approach, to tackle the issues of corrupted data, a robust aggregation method (Pillutla et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Pillutla K, Kakade SM, Harchaoui Z (2022) Robust aggregation for federated learning. IEEE Trans Signal Process 70:1142–1154. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TSP.2022.3153135&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR112" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2928">2022</a>) was used, in which the aggregation was performed in two ways, viz. a one-step aggregation in the global model and another on device personalization aggregation. Due to the multiple local updates and consistency between the targeted distribution, the authors’ proposed unbiased gradient variant (Yao et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Yao X, Huang T, Zhang R-X, Li R, Sun L (2020) Federated learning with unbiased gradient aggregation and controllable meta updating. &#xA;                  arXiv:1910.08234&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR165" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2931">2020</a>) aggregation method was used, and using this method, faster convergence and higher accuracy were achieved. The author of Palihawadana et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Palihawadana C, Wiratunga N, Wijekoon A, Kalutarage H (2022) FedSim: similarity guided model aggregation for federated learning. Neurocomputing 483:432–445. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neucom.2021.08.141&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR108" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2934">2022</a>) proposed a FedSim aggregation model for local and global aggregation. In this method, at first, similar gradients were clustered using local aggregation and then globally aggregated for better convergence and variance. In a similar vein, the quality of the gradients was provided by the analog gradient aggregation (Guo et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Guo H, Liu A, Lau VKN (2021) Analog gradient aggregation for federated learning over wireless networks: customized design and convergence analysis. IEEE Internet Things J 8(1):197–210. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2020.3002925&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR35" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2937">2021</a>) for learning over wireless using SGD. A summary of the above aggregation methods has been presented in Table <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Tab4">4</a>.</p><p>For securing the aggregation process, HeteroSAg was introduced (Zhang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2023b" title="Zhang J, Li X, Gu K, Liang W, Li K (2023b) Secure aggregation in heterogeneous federated learning for digital ecosystems. IEEE Trans Consum Electron" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR179" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2947">2023b</a>) using heterogeneous quantization. The edge users adjusted their quantization to available resources using HeteroSAg and achieved the best trade-off between accuracy and communication costs. Similarly, for secure aggregation and robustness against client dropping out, it was introduced in the federated environments (Eltaras et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2023" title="Eltaras T, Sabry F, Labda W, Alzoubi K, Ahmedeltaras Q (2023) Efficient verifiable protocol for privacy-preserving aggregation in federated learning. IEEE Trans Inf Forensics Secur 18:2977–2990" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR30" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2950">2023</a>). To address the security challenges in a centralized aggregation, a trustworthy aggregation model called DeTA (Cheng et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2024" title="Cheng P-C, Eykholt K, Gu Z, Jamjoom H, Jayaram K, Valdez E, Verma A (2024) Deta: minimizing data leaks in federated learning via decentralized and trustworthy aggregation. In: Proceedings of the nineteenth european conference on computer systems, pp 219–235" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR16" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2953">2024</a>) was introduced, using the DETA multi-aggregation method used in the FL ecosystem. The model was aggregated using this approach without any alteration. This resulted in improved privacy. Similarly, for better privacy in the distributed environment, the DOTFL method was introduced using a neural network. Malicious activities were detected in the FL system using the DOTFL. To personalize FL, a local federated learning-based method called FedALA was introduced to impair the generalization of the global model. Another important issue in FL is limited bandwidth and energy in the distributed environment (Zhang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2023a" title="Zhang J, Hua Y, Wang H, Song T, Xue Z, Ma R, Guan H (2023a) Fedala: adaptive local aggregation for personalized federated learning. In: Proceedings of the AAAI conference on artificial intelligence, vol 37, pp 11237–11244" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR178" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2956">2023a</a>). To address this, particle aggregation was introduced, and the model is called PMA-FL in the wireless environment (Chen et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2024" title="Chen Z, Yi W, Shin H, Nallanathan A, Li GY (2024) Efficient wireless federated learning with partial model aggregation. IEEE Trans Commun" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR20" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2959">2024</a>). Using the PMA-FL, the features extraction part was shared for prediction and the learning process.</p><p><b>Relationship Between Node Selection and Aggregation</b> The efficiency of FL heavily depends on how well the node selection methods and aggregation methods have been integrated. These two functions need to be carefully synchronized to manage communication costs and data integrity in the system. The main node selection methods that have been considered are random selection, importance-based selection, resource-awareness based selection, specific criteria-based selection and reward-based selection. The random selection method is fair but not efficient, and aggregation without efficiency would lead to increased communication costs and efficiency. The importance based, resource-awareness-based and reward-based selection methods demonstrate more effective selection with regards to clients in a distributed environment. This produces better aggregation results globally with reduced communication costs in terms of measuring the quality of data, measuring the capability of the training data, and encouraging better participation. The specific criteria-based selection creates data groups based on certain criteria and the selection is done proportionally from each group of data. This helps in dealing with data heterogeneity in disparate environments.</p><p>Furthermore, by considering a local aggregation methods, data quality is improved since it results in locally updated and similarly clustered data that is globally aggregated, resulting in reduced communication costs. Therefore, resource-awareness based selection, specific criteria-based selection and reward-based selection methods, combined with local aggregation methods provide reduced frequency of communication, and result in a better performance model in collaborative environments (Alferaidi et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Alferaidi A, Yadav K, Alharbi Y, Viriyasitavat W, Kautish S, Dhiman G (2022) Federated learning algorithms to optimize the client and cost selections. Math Probl Eng 2022(1):8514562" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR5" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2971">2022</a>). Careful integration of node selection and aggregation methods in federated learning is crucial for optimizing communication costs and handling data heterogeneity. Thoughtful designing and aligning of these methods can help in increasing the efficiency and performance of federated learning systems (Wu and Wang <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Wu H, Wang P (2022) Node selection toward faster convergence for federated learning on non-iid data. IEEE Trans Netw Sci Eng 9(5):3099–3111" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR150" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2974">2022</a>).</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Knowledge transfer methods"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec4-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec4"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">4 </span>Knowledge transfer methods</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec4-content"><p>Knowledge transfer enables the smooth transmission of knowledge from one domain (source) to another domain (target) for better propagation of learning even under starkly different situations (Li et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020b" title="Li L, Fan Y, Lin K-Y (2020b) A Survey on federated learning. In: 2020 IEEE 16th international conference on control &amp; automation (ICCA), pp 791–796. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICCA51439.2020.9264412&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 1948-3457" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR73" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2985">2020b</a>; Yang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019a" title="Yang Q, Liu Y, Chen T, Tong Y (2019a) Federated machine learning: concept and applications. ACM Trans Intell Syst Technol 10(2):12–11219. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3298981&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR161" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2988">2019a</a>). The authors of Yang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019a" title="Yang Q, Liu Y, Chen T, Tong Y (2019a) Federated machine learning: concept and applications. ACM Trans Intell Syst Technol 10(2):12–11219. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3298981&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR161" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2991">2019a</a>), Saha and Ahmad (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Saha S, Ahmad T (2021) Federated transfer learning: concept and applications. &#xA;                  arXiv:2010.15561&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR126" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e2994">2021</a>) categorized federated learning into three groups: horizontal, vertical, and transfer federated learning. In the case of horizontal FL, an overlap of certain features can be observed across the different nodes. Moreover, the same feature dimension is used across all nodes. In contrast, the features of a vertical FL include a vertical dimension. For example, a problem may have the same entities but different characters. In the case of federated transfer learning, the knowledge is transferred into a different domain altogether. Hence the federated knowledge transfer differs radically from the vertical and horizontal knowledge transfer.</p><p>In this section, various works related to federated knowledge transfer have been presented. Federated knowledge transfer is widely used in applications across different verticals and areas such as industrial, healthcare, security, and user privacy, etc. Therefore, a fairly diverse set of applications are found to use knowledge transfer for sharing of features for better results. The diagrammatic representation of knowledge transfer in FL is presented in the Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Fig5">5</a>. The process of step by step knowledge transfer representation shown in Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Fig6">6</a>.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-5" data-title="Fig. 5"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig5" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 5</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig5_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-5-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig5_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 5" loading="lazy" width="685" height="355"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/figures/5" data-track-dest="link:Figure5 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 5" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-5-desc"><p>Federated knowledge transfer (Yang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019a" title="Yang Q, Liu Y, Chen T, Tong Y (2019a) Federated machine learning: concept and applications. ACM Trans Intell Syst Technol 10(2):12–11219. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3298981&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR161" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3018">2019a</a>; Saha and Ahmad <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Saha S, Ahmad T (2021) Federated transfer learning: concept and applications. &#xA;                  arXiv:2010.15561&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR126" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3021">2021</a>)</p></div></div></figure></div><p>Further, different knowledge transfer techniques related to federated learning is presented along with their corresponding limitations. A summary of the different techniques, goals, implementation details and metrics has been presented in Table <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Tab5">5</a>. The author of Li et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022d" title="Li C, Li G, Varshney PK (2022d) Decentralized federated learning via mutual knowledge transfer. IEEE Internet Things J 9(2):1136–1147. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2021.3078543&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR70" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3038">2022d</a>) demonstrated a decentralized FL utilizing mutual knowledge sharing by using Def-KT, wherein the local client transferred their learning knowledge to other nodes. The combo and full average were used for averaging in the IoT system. In this work, the communication cost was seen to be high. In another instance, a group knowledge transfer was performed using the federated learning method called FedGKT (He et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="He C, Annavaram M, Avestimehr S (2020) Group knowledge transfer: federated learning of large CNNs at the edge. In: Advances in neural information processing systems, vol 33. Curran Associates, Inc., pp. 14068–14080. &#xA;                  https://proceedings.neurips.cc/paper/2020/hash/a1d4c20b182ad7137ab3606f0e3fc8a4-Abstract.html&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR39" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3041">2020</a>). Using FedGKT, the resource constraint problem was addressed in the edge devices with knowledge transfer formulated using edge devices. Personalized federated learning was performed using parametrized knowledge transfer (KT-pFL). In KT-pFL, the personalized soft prediction was maintained by using local training and collaborating with different clients using similar dimensions. The communication round, efficiency and accuracy were considered for evaluating KT-pFL.</p><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-5"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab5" data-test="table-caption">Table 5 Summary of knowledge transfer methods</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/tables/5" aria-label="Full size table 5"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><p>To avoid round communication, the authors of Li et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020c" title="Li Q, He B, Song D (2020c) Model-agnostic round-optimal federated learning via knowledge transfer. Accessed 17 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR74" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3432">2020c</a>) proposed a model called round optimal FL via knowledge transfer where optimal agnostic accuracy was increased and privacy loss was reduced. The authors of Zhang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Zhang L, Wu D, Yuan X (2022b) FedZKT: zero-shot knowledge transfer towards resource-constrained federated learning with heterogeneous on-device models. &#xA;                  arXiv:2109.03775&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR183" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3435">2022</a>) proposed a model called zero-shot knowledge (FedZKT) transfer. This method proposed the transfer of knowledge across the heterogeneous models in a data-free manner in distributed devices. In another instance, the authors of Cho et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Cho YJ, Wang J, Chiruvolu T, Joshi G (2021) Personalized federated learning for heterogeneous clients with clustered knowledge transfer. &#xA;                  arXiv:2109.08119&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR23" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3438">2021</a>) presented a clustered knowledge (PERFED-CKT) transfer for similar data distribution in personalized devices using the clustered data distribution, reducing the communication cost, and increasing the accuracy. The authors of Nguyen et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022a" title="Nguyen MNH, Le HQ, Pandey SR, Hong CS (2022a) CDKT-FL: cross-device knowledge transfer using proxy dataset in federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:2204.01542&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR98" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3441">2022a</a>) proposed a cross-device knowledge transfer for global knowledge and on-device. This model was observed to successfully speedup and personalize the performance of the client model. In this work, the FedAvg algorithm was used for training and for minimizing the communication load when exchanging the models. To train the large server using small and heterogenous clients, authors of Cho et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Cho YJ, Manoel A, Joshi G, Sim R, Dimitriadis D (2022) Heterogeneous ensemble knowledge transfer for training large models in federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:2204.12703&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR22" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3444">2022</a>) proposed the Fed-ET. Three consecutive steps were used to manage the Fed-ET such as local training and translator, weighted diversity regulation, and server transfer. Using this method communication efficiency was increased.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-6" data-title="Fig. 6"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig6" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 6</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig6_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-6-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig6_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 6" loading="lazy" width="685" height="341"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/figures/6" data-track-dest="link:Figure6 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 6" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-6-desc"><p>Federated knowledge transfer steps</p></div></div></figure></div><p>The authors of Yu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Yu S, Nguyen P, Abebe W, Anwar A, Jannesari A (2021) SPATL: salient parameter aggregation and transfer learning for heterogeneous clients in federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:2111.14345&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR174" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3469">2021</a>) proposed a SPATL model for knowledge transfer and feature selection in heterogenous client using local updates. The authors of Zhang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022a" title="Zhang L, Shen L, Ding L, Tao D, Duan L-Y (2022a) Fine-tuning global model via data-free knowledge distillation for non-IID federated learning. In: The IEEE/CVF computer vision and pattern recognition conference (CVPR), New Orleans, Louisiana, USA, p 4. IEEE" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR181" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3472">2022a</a>) proposed a model called FedFTG for knowledge distillation to fine-tune global models using local models. The local model was transferred to the global model in heterogeneous scenarios. The authors of Le et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Le HQ, Shin JH, Nguyen MNH, Hong CS (2021) Distilling knowledge in federated learning. In: 2021 22nd asia-pacific network operations and management symposium (APNOMS), pp 196–201. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.23919/APNOMS52696.2021.9562670&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2576-8565" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR62" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3475">2021</a>) proposed a soft target for the reference dataset model called FedBD. The knowledge distribution minimized the gap between server and local devices after output was received from the clients. The client updated the local model by training the reference and private data using this model for knowledge distillation. The authors of Wu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Wu C, Wu F, Lyu L, Huang Y, Xie X (2022) FedKD: communication efficient federated learning via knowledge distillation. Nat Commun 13(1):2032. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1038/s41467-022-29763-x&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR151" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3478">2022</a>) also proposed knowledge distillation for effective communication in federated learning. The FedKD model with an adaptive mutual distillation was used for effective collaboration and communication. The authors of Chang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Chang H, Shejwalkar V, Shokri R, Houmansadr A (2019) Cronus: robust and heterogeneous collaborative learning with black-box knowledge transfer. &#xA;                  arXiv:1912.11279&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR12" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3481">2019</a>), Pei et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Pei X, Deng X, Tian S, Zhang L, Xue K (2022) A knowledge transfer-based semi-supervised federated learning for IoT malware detection. IEEE Trans Depend Secur Comput. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TDSC.2022.3173664&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR110" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3485">2022</a>), Pan et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Pan Y, Ni J, Su Z (2021) FL-PATE: differentially private federated learning with knowledge transfer. In: 2021 IEEE global communications conference (GLOBECOM), pp 1–6. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/GLOBECOM46510.2021.9685079&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR109" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3488">2021</a>), Qi et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Qi T, Wu F, Wu C, Huang Y, Xie X (2022) Differentially private knowledge transfer for federated learning. preprint, In Review . &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.21203/rs.3.rs-1571398/v1&#xA;                  &#xA;                . &#xA;                  https://www.researchsquare.com/article/rs-1571398/v1&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR116" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3491">2022</a>), Shi and Radu (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Shi H, Radu V (2021) Towards federated learning with attention transfer to mitigate system and data heterogeneity of clients. In: Proceedings of the 4th international workshop on edge systems, analytics and networking. EdgeSys ’21. Association for Computing Machinery, New York, NY, USA, pp 61–66. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3434770.3459739&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 16 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR132" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3494">2021</a>), Zhao et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Zhao Y, Chen J, Guo Q, Teng J, Wu D (2020) Network anomaly detection using federated learning and transfer learning. In: Yu S, Mueller P, Qianq J (eds) Security and privacy in digital economy. communications in computer and information science. Springer, Singapore, pp 219–231. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-981-15-9129-7_16&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR185" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3497">2020</a>), Li et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022f" title="Li J, Rakin AS, Chen X, He Z, Fan D, Chakrabarti, C (2022f) ResSFL: a resistance transfer framework for defending model inversion attack in split federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:2205.04007&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR79" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3500">2022f</a>) used knowledge transfer to manage private data, malware detection, anomaly detection and dependency, as well as inversion attack using collaborative machine learning.</p><p>The traditional horizontal federated learning (FL) is affected by non-IID distributions. To improve the personalized private learning model, the proposed pFedKT framework (Yi et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2024" title="Yi L, Shi X, Wang N, Wang G, Liu X, Shi Z, Yu H (2024) pfedkt: personalized federated learning with dual knowledge transfer. Knowl-Based Syst 292:111633" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR167" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3506">2024</a>) for private and global knowledge transfer is introduced. In pFedKT, two types of knowledge transfer are achieved using hypernetworks for transferring historical data into a new private model and contrastive learning for transferring global model knowledge into a private model for improved accuracy. Similarly, while the same horizontal federated learning protects the local private data of each participant, it is not sufficient for the learning model. To overcome this issue, FedKT (Wang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2024a" title="Wang Z, Xiao J, Wang L, Yao J (2024a) A novel federated learning approach with knowledge transfer for credit scoring. Decis Support Syst 177:114084" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR142" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3509">2024a</a>) uses fine-tuning and knowledge extraction from the early layers of processing. To achieve sustainable development, a new knowledge level introduces four sources: tasks, features, models, and algorithms (Wang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2024b" title="Wang L, Zhao Y, Dong J, Yin A, Li Q, Wang X, Niyato D, Zhu Q (2024b) Federated learning with new knowledge: fundamentals, advances, and futures. arXiv preprint &#xA;                  arXiv:2402.02268&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR148" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3512">2024b</a>). It also introduces new federated continual learning for the transmission of knowledge. To share secure knowledge in a distributed environment, the KD-IS (Shi et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2024" title="Shi Z, Li Y, Liu C (2024) Knowledge distillation-based information sharing for online process monitoring in decentralized manufacturing system. J Intell Manuf 1–16" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR129" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3515">2024</a>) framework is introduced for monitoring poor performance models.</p><p><b>Discussion</b> It is evident from the above summary that the features and data characteristics in question have been are changing from client to client based on various criteria. In essence, in federated learning, managing of clients, effective learning, and updating of knowledge transfer methods need to evolve further based on specific criteria. As far as knowledge transfer is concerned, communication cost, communication rounds, balancing the clients and maintaining privacy during knowledge transfer, as well as managing the energy expenditure are the essential factors to be considered in knowledge sharing.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Data management"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec5-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec5"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">5 </span>Data management</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec5-content"><p>In federated learning, data collection and behavior property are based on the non-IID. Non-IID means non-independent and identical distribution. In the federated learning data, the collection of the random variables with independent and identical distributed random variables has the same probability and is mutually independent. The different data properties and characteristics are presented in Ma et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Ma X, Zhu J, Lin Z, Chen S, Qin Y (2022) A state-of-the-art survey on solving non-IID data in Federated Learning. Futur Gener Comput Syst 135:244–258. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.future.2022.05.003&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR92" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3531">2022</a>) but do not describe the different methods for managing non-IID data. The non-IID in the federated learning method manages data sharing, selection, enhancement, data updation, algorithm-based learning such as meta, multi-tasking, and lifelong learning, and classification of data based on similarity, knowledge distillation, and personalization. Figure <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Fig7">7</a> presents non-IID data management related to health care. In Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Fig7">7</a>, the different clients have identical, and the data distribution is also different.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-7" data-title="Fig. 7"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig7" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 7</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig7_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-7-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig7_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 7" loading="lazy" width="685" height="345"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/figures/7" data-track-dest="link:Figure7 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 7" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-7-desc"><p>Data management (non-IID)</p></div></div></figure></div><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-6"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab6" data-test="table-caption">Table 6 Summary of data management (Non-IID)</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/tables/6" aria-label="Full size table 6"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><p>Different methods are present to manage the non-IID data in federated learning. A summary of the different techniques, goals, datasets, and metrics has been presented in Table <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Tab6">6</a>. The authors of Briggs et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Briggs C, Fan Z, Andras P (2020) Federated learning with hierarchical clustering of local updates to improve training on non-IID data. In: 2020 international joint conference on neural networks (IJCNN), pp 1–9. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/IJCNN48605.2020.9207469&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2161-4407" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR10" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3916">2020</a>) present a method to improve the non-IID data training in local updates using the FL + HL method. In this method, the data is clustered based on the similarity of local data. The pairwise collaboration of similar data between the clients is managed using the FedAMP (Huang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Huang Y, Chu L, Zhou Z, Wang L, Liu J, Pei J, Zhang Y (2021) Personalized cross-silo federated learning on non-IID data. In: Proceedings of the AAAI conference on artificial intelligence, vol 35, pp 7865–7873. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1609/aaai.v35i9.16960&#xA;                  &#xA;                . &#xA;                  https://ojs.aaai.org/index.php/AAAI/article/view/16960&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR48" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3919">2021</a>) method. The authors of Li et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022e" title="Li Q, Diao Y, Chen Q, He B (2022e) Federated learning on non-IID data silos: an experimental study. In: 2022 IEEE 38th international conference on data engineering (ICDE), pp 965–978. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICDE53745.2022.00077&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2375-026X" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR72" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3922">2022e</a>) present a comprehensive partitioning of different non-IID data case strategies to manage heterogeneous data distribution in different parties, and the authors of Zhao et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Zhao Z, Feng C, Hong W, Jiang J, Jia C, Quek TQS, Peng M (2022) Federated learning with non-IID data in wireless networks. IEEE Trans Wirel Commun 21(3):1927–1942. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TWC.2021.3108197&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR184" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3925">2022</a>) present non-IID data user behavior in the 6 G wireless environment using federated learning. The authors Chen et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020b" title="Chen Y, Ning Y, Slawski M, Rangwala H (2020b) Asynchronous online federated learning for edge devices with non-IID data. In: 2020 IEEE international conference on big data (Big Data), pp 15–24. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/BigData50022.2020.9378161&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR18" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3929">2020b</a>) present an ASO-fed method for managing heterogeneous devices and sampling data in edge devices. In this work volume of data, varying latency and availability issues are considered. The authors of Itahara et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Itahara S, Nishio T, Koda Y, Morikura M, Yamamoto K (2021) Distillation-based semi-supervised federated learning for communication-efficient collaborative training with non-IID private data. IEEE Trans Mob Comput. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TMC.2021.3070013&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR50" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3932">2021</a>) proposed the DS-FL method to exchange the output of local data, manage the ambiguity of data samples, and manage training convergence. Using this method reduces the communication cost and achieves better classification of similar data. FedCD (Kopparapu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Kopparapu K, Lin E, Zhao J (2020) FedCD: improving performance in non-IID federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:2006.09637&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR58" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3935">2020</a>) dynamically groups similar data in different clients. Using the FedCD method, higher accuracy, fast convergence, and manageable overhead problems in federated learning. Similarly, the author of Onoszko et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Onoszko N Karlsson, G Mogren O, Zec EL (2021) Decentralized federated learning of deep neural networks on non-iid data. &#xA;                  arXiv:2107.08517&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR106" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3938">2021</a>) proposed a method called PENS and, using this work, similar data distribution in clients and evaluated the training losses in federated learning. The authors of Li et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021d" title="Li X, Jiang M, Zhang X, Kamp M, Dou Q (2021d) FedBN: federated learning on non-IID features via local batch normalization. &#xA;                  arXiv:2102.07623&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR76" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3941">2021d</a>) proposed a method called FedBN for normalizing the client data and shifting the features of the data before aggregation. The authors of Chen et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Chen M, Mao B, Ma T (2021a) FedSA: a staleness-aware asynchronous Federated Learning algorithm with non-IID data. Futur Gener Comput Syst 120:1–12. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.future.2021.02.012&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR15" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3944">2021a</a>) and Zhang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021c" title="Zhang L, Luo Y, Bai Y, Du B, Duan L-Y (2021c) Federated learning for non-IID data via unified feature learning and optimization objective alignment. In: 2021 IEEE/CVF international conference on computer vision (ICCV), pp 4400–4408. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICCV48922.2021.00438&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2380-7504" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR180" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3948">2021c</a>) proposed a method called FedSA (Chen et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Chen M, Mao B, Ma T (2021a) FedSA: a staleness-aware asynchronous Federated Learning algorithm with non-IID data. Futur Gener Comput Syst 120:1–12. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.future.2021.02.012&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR15" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3951">2021a</a>) and FedUFO (Zhang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021c" title="Zhang L, Luo Y, Bai Y, Du B, Duan L-Y (2021c) Federated learning for non-IID data via unified feature learning and optimization objective alignment. In: 2021 IEEE/CVF international conference on computer vision (ICCV), pp 4400–4408. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICCV48922.2021.00438&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2380-7504" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR180" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3954">2021c</a>) to manage unstable, unreliable, inconsistentency, and feature divergence problems in distributed non-IID. Using these two methods, the learning performance is increased in federated learning. And also, the authors of Zhang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Zhang M, Wang Y, Luo T (2020) Federated learning for arrhythmia detection of non-IID ECG. In: 2020 IEEE 6th international conference on computer and communications (ICCC), pp 1176–1180. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICCC51575.2020.9344971&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR182" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3957">2020</a>) proposed a method to diagnose and detect arrhythmia using non-IID ECG. Using this method, medical institutions can collaboratively train and detect arrhythmia using federated learning. The optimized data management method introduced in the distributed environment is called ODMSM-FL (Ramani et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2024" title="Ramani R, Mary AR, Raja SE, Shunmugam DA (2024) Optimized data management and secured federated learning in the internet of medical things (IOMT) with blockchain technology. Biomed Signal Process Control 93:106213" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR119" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3960">2024</a>). This method achieves secure federated learning in the distributed environment using blockchain technology.</p><p><b>Discussion</b> The data distribution with a non-IID and personalized FL has a number of potential issues. The major challenges with non-IID data distribution are divergence in local models for making aggregations into a global model, slower convergence rate due to non-IID data, biased global models due to certain data distribution and inconsistent contribution issues due to variability in the training process. Personalized federated learning provides better privacy, with stronger privacy algorithms required. Beyond that, model personalization and globalization, resource constraints, scalability, and complexity of implementation are some of the potential issues in data distribution and personalized federated learning.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Incentives"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec6-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec6"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">6 </span>Incentives</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec6-content"><p>Incentive mechanisms in FL refer to the improvement in the quality of data resulting in better accuracy with fewer iterations, thus leading to better overall efficiency and energy-saving measures. The authors of Abdulrahman et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Abdulrahman S, Tout H, Ould-Slimane H, Mourad A, Talhi C, Guizani M (2021a) A survey on federated learning: the journey from centralized to distributed on-site learning and beyond. IEEE Internet Things J 8(7):5476–5497. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2020.3030072&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR1" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3978">2021a</a>), Tu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Tu X, Zhu K, Luong NC, Niyato D, Zhang Y, Li J (2022) Incentive mechanisms for federated learning: from economic and game theoretic perspective. IEEE Trans Cogn Commun Netw. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TCCN.2022.3177522&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR137" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3981">2022</a>), Seon Hong et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Seon Hong C, Khan LU, Chen M, Chen D, Saad W, Han Z (2021) Incentive mechanisms for federated learning. In: Hong CS, Khan LU, Chen M, Chen D, Saad W, Han Z (eds) Federated learning for wireless networks. Wireless networks. Springer, Singapore, pp 71–128. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-981-16-4963-9_4&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR128" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3984">2021</a>) described such an incentive mechanism that would reward efforts towards achieving a higher quality of data. The authors of Seon Hong et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Seon Hong C, Khan LU, Chen M, Chen D, Saad W, Han Z (2021) Incentive mechanisms for federated learning. In: Hong CS, Khan LU, Chen M, Chen D, Saad W, Han Z (eds) Federated learning for wireless networks. Wireless networks. Springer, Singapore, pp 71–128. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-981-16-4963-9_4&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR128" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3987">2021</a>) provided an incentive mechanism related to the design of federated learning and chose to use game theory and action theory for designing the incentive mechanism. In order to manage false results on the local data and to determine the truthiness of the client, the authors of Liu and Wei (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Liu Y, Wei J (2020) Incentives for federated learning: a hypothesis elicitation approach. &#xA;                  arXiv:2007.10596&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 7 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR85" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3990">2020</a>) decided to introduce a solution based on the Bayesian Nash equilibrium framework. Using this model, the real client truth was verified. The authors of Sun et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Sun W, Xu N, Wang L, Zhang H, Zhang Y (2022) Dynamic digital twin and federated learning with incentives for air-ground networks. IEEE Trans Netw Sci Eng 9(1):321–333. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TNSE.2020.3048137&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR134" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3994">2022</a>) proposed a static and dynamic design for building an incentive mechanism for federated learning using the real-time status of the network elements that assisted the design using FL. The authors of Richardson et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Richardson A, Filos-Ratsikas A, Faltings B (2020) Budget-bounded incentives for federated learning. In: Yang Q, Fan L, Yu H (eds) Federated learning: privacy and incentive. Lecture Notes in Computer Science. Springer, Cham, pp 176–188. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-63076-8_13&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR122" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e3997">2020</a>) proposed a game-theoretic scheme for finding the truthiness of data and for reducing data redundancy. Similarly, the authors of Chen et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020a" title="Chen Z, Liu Z, Ng KL, Yu H, Liu Y, Yang Q (2020a) A gamified research tool for incentive mechanism design in federated learning. In: Yang Q, Fan L, Yu H (eds) Federated learning: privacy and incentive. Lecture Notes in Computer Science. Springer, Cham, pp 168–175. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-63076-8_12&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 7 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR17" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4000">2020a</a>) used a gamified research tool to manage the high-quality data in the FL eco-system. The authors of Wang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Wang Y, Su Z, Luan T, Li R, Zhang K (2021a) Federated learning with fair incentives and robust aggregation for UAV-aided crowdsensing. IEEE Trans Netw Sci Eng. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TNSE.2021.3138928&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR139" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4003">2021a</a>) presented a fair and robust federated learning (FRFL) to address the incentive mismatch and free-rider attack for UAVs. The authors of Yu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Yu H, Liu Z, Liu Y, Chen T, Cong M, Weng X, Niyato D, Yang Q (2020) A fairness-aware incentive scheme for federated learning. In: Proceedings of the AAAI/ACM conference on AI, ethics, and society. AIES ’20. Association for Computing Machinery, New York, NY, USA, pp. 393–399. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3375627.3375840&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 6 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR173" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4006">2020</a>) proposed an FLI (Federated learning incentivizer) to maximize the collectiveness of the data and to minimize data inequalities in FL. In the context of competitive situations, the role of incentives in federated learning cannot be overstated. Clients are motivated to participate in information gathering, which in turn reduces the cost and resources required. This is achieved through three key components (Sim et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2024" title="Sim RHL, Tay SS, Xu X, Zhang Y, Wu Z, Lin X, Ng S-K, Foo C-S, Jaillet P, Hoang TN, et al (2024) Incentives in federated learning. In: Federated learning. Elsevier, Amsterdam, pp 299–309" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR133" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4009">2024</a>)in the shared environment: fair contribution of client data, client selection to maximize the global model, and reward-based allocation to clients. The higher rewards provide better outcomes. The summary of the incentive methods is presented in Table <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Tab7">7</a>.</p><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-7"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab7" data-test="table-caption">Table 7 Summary of incentive methods</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/tables/7" aria-label="Full size table 7"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><p><b>Discussion</b> High-quality client data is required to manage fast convergence and effective global models (Abdulrahman et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Abdulrahman S, Tout H, Ould-Slimane H, Mourad A, Talhi C, Guizani M (2021a) A survey on federated learning: the journey from centralized to distributed on-site learning and beyond. IEEE Internet Things J 8(7):5476–5497. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2020.3030072&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR1" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4243">2021a</a>). A practical incentivizing approach is required for managing the client’s data and to this end, the verification of the client’s data density, data update, and the influence of new data must be considered in building new incentive approaches.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Communication cost"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec7-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec7"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">7 </span>Communication cost</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec7-content"><p>Continuous communication in federated learning requires an extensive number of communication rounds between the client and server due to the sizeable data and number of clients. This necessitates the use of effective algorithms and models to reduce the cost between the client and the global model (Kang and Ahn <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Kang D, Ahn CW (2021) Communication cost reduction with partial structure in federated learning. Electronics 10(17):2081. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.3390/electronics10172081&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR54" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4254">2021</a>). To that end, a number of approaches have been used to decrease communication rounds and improve performance. The Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Fig8">8</a> represents the number of rounds and communication differences between high and low communication costs.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-8" data-title="Fig. 8"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig8" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 8</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig8_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-8-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig8_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 8" loading="lazy" width="685" height="431"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/figures/8" data-track-dest="link:Figure8 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 8" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-8-desc"><p>Communication cost representation</p></div></div></figure></div><p>The authors of Konečný et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2017" title="Konečný J, McMahan HB, Yu FX, Richtárik P, Suresh AT, Bacon D (2017) Federated learning: strategies for improving communication efficiency. &#xA;                  arXiv:1610.05492&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 9 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR57" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4282">2017</a>) proposed two approaches to manage communication cost, such as structured and sketched updates. The structured approach restricted updates such as low rank and random mask in two ways. The sketched update, on the other hand, compressed the trained data before sending to the server. The compression was performed using subsampling, random rotation, and quantization. Similarly, approaches like CMFL, and ADMM (WANG et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Wang L, Wang W, Li B (2019) CMFL: mitigating communication overhead for federated learning. In: 2019 IEEE 39th international conference on distributed computing systems (ICDCS), pp 954–964. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICDCS.2019.00099&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2575-8411" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR144" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4285">2019</a>; Zhou and Li <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Zhou S, Li GY (2022) Communication-efficient ADMM-based federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:2110.15318&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 9 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR190" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4288">2022</a>) have been used to identify the irrelevant updates and to reduce the client footprint. Such reduction of communication overheads such as irrelevant updates guaranteed learning convergence. The authors of Yao et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Yao X, Huang T, Wu C, Zhang R, Sun L (2019) Towards faster and better federated learning: a feature fusion approach. In: 2019 IEEE international conference on image processing (ICIP), pp 175–179. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICIP.2019.8803001&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2381-8549" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR164" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4291">2019</a>) proposed a features fusion method to manage the federated FedAvg communication cost and performance drops between local and global models. The authors of Dai et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Dai X, Yan X, Zhou K, Yang H, Ng KKW, Cheng J, Fan Y (2019) Hyper-sphere quantization: communication-efficient SGD for federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:1911.04655&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 9 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR26" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4294">2019</a>) proposed a method for a hyper-sphere quantization framework for achieving a better trade-off between communication and gradient accuracy with different configurations.</p><p>The quantization method has been effectively used for compression. Similarly, the adapting FedAvg and Adam optimization has been used to reduce the communication cost using compression techniques. The FedPAQ (Reisizadeh et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Reisizadeh A, Mokhtari A, Hassani H, Jadbabaie A, Pedarsani R (2020) FedPAQ: a communication-efficient federated learning method with periodic averaging and quantization. In: Proceedings of the twenty third international conference on artificial intelligence and statistics, pp 2021–2031. PMLR. ISSN: 2640-3498. &#xA;                  https://proceedings.mlr.press/v108/reisizadeh20a.html&#xA;                  &#xA;                 Accessed 9 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR121" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4300">2020</a>) method was seen to effectively manage the computation using three features such as periodically updating the local device to the server device, involving particle devices for training, quantization of messages to the server. These three parameters have helped address the communication cost and scalability of federated learning. The FetchSGD (Rothchild et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Rothchild D, Panda A, Ullah E, Ivkin N, Stoica I, Braverman V, Gonzalez J, Arora R (2020) FetchSGD: communication-efficient federated learning with sketching. In: Proceedings of the 37th international conference on machine learning, pp 8253–8265. PMLR. ISSN: 2640-3498. &#xA;                  https://proceedings.mlr.press/v119/rothchild20a.html&#xA;                  &#xA;                 Accessed 9 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR125" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4303">2020</a>) method has similarly addressed the communication bottleneck and convergence issues in federated learning using sketching. The momentum and error accumulation were carried out in the sketch. The top-k extracted the information from the local client and broadcasted it. The authors of Hamer et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Hamer J, Mohri M, Suresh AT (2020) FedBoost: a communication-efficient algorithm for federated learning. In: Proceedings of the 37th international conference on machine learning, pp 3973–3983. PMLR. ISSN: 2640-3498. &#xA;                  https://proceedings.mlr.press/v119/hamer20a.html&#xA;                  &#xA;                 Accessed 9 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR38" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4306">2020</a>) proposed an ensemble-based algorithm for managing communication efficiency with the gradient commutation methods. The ensemble-based algorithm reduced client-to-server and server-to-client communication costs. For reducing the upstream and downstream communication costs in federating learning, the T-FedAvg (Xu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022a" title="Xu J, Du W, Jin Y, He W, Cheng R (2022a) Ternary compression for communication-efficient federated learning. IEEE Trans Neural Netw Learn Syst 33(3):1162–1176. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TNNLS.2020.3041185&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR158" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4309">2022a</a>) method was used. The author of Li et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Li C, Li G, Varshney PK (2021b) Communication-efficient federated learning based on compressed sensing. IEEE Internet Things J 8(20):15531–15541. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2021.3073112&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR66" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4312">2021b</a>) proposed a compressed sensing federated algorithm (CS-FL) to manage downstream and upstream communication between clients and servers. The proposed CS-FL algorithm was compressed with former basic algorithms such as FedAvg and SignSGD.</p><div class="c-article-table" data-test="inline-table" data-container-section="table" id="table-8"><figure><figcaption class="c-article-table__figcaption"><b id="Tab8" data-test="table-caption">Table 8 Summary of communication cost reduction methods</b></figcaption><div class="u-text-right u-hide-print"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="table-link" data-track="click" data-track-action="view table" data-track-label="button" rel="nofollow" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/tables/8" aria-label="Full size table 8"><span>Full size table</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></figure></div><p>Using the ternary federated protocol, both the direction data was compressed, and the energy compression reduced. The authors of Nguyen et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Nguyen HT, Sehwag V, Hosseinalipour S, Brinton CG, Chiang M, Vincent Poor H (2021a) Fast-convergent federated learning. IEEE J Sel Areas Commun 39(1):201–218. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JSAC.2020.3036952&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR99" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4798">2021a</a>) proposed a fast convergence algorithm for decreasing the communication rounds and increasing the accuracy of communication. The proposed FOLB algorithm was found to handle communication and heterogeneous devices effectively and to estimate the capabilities of updates. This work increased the model accuracy, convergence speed and model stability across the learning task. Different approaches for the ease of management of the communication burden in IoT systems have been proposed using federated learning with the help of quantization and scarification methods. The authors of Liu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022a" title="Liu S, Yu J, Deng X, Wan S (2022a) FedCPF: an efficient-communication federated learning approach for vehicular edge computing in 6G communication networks. IEEE Trans Intell Transp Syst 23(2):1616–1629. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TITS.2021.3099368&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR82" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4801">2022a</a>) proposed a method for tackling the communication costs of expensive in-vehicle networks. In another instance, the authors proposed the FedCPF method for customized local training to achieve convergence within a few communication rounds. Similarly, uplink congestion introduced the practice of partial client participation to avoid numerous updates. Compared to the traditional base method (FedAvg) was found to achieve better testing accuracy and communication optimization. In a similar vein, the authors of Wu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Wu C, Wu F, Lyu L, Huang Y, Xie X (2022) FedKD: communication efficient federated learning via knowledge distillation. Nat Commun 13(1):2032. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1038/s41467-022-29763-x&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR151" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4804">2022</a>) proposed an efficient federated learning method for effective communication using knowledge distillation. With all the work done in this field till now in mind, the author’s proposed method, called the fedKD framework has been found to effectively reduce communication cost without any notable performance sacrifices. The proposed FedKD exchanges the local updates of a small model, rather than the original model, thus reducing the communication cost using a mentee and mentor relationship. The FedKD framework was evaluated using different scenarios and was found to reduce 94.89% of the communication cost and achieved comparatively better results in a global model. The authors of Asad et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Asad M, Moustafa A, Ito T, Aslam M (2021) Evaluating the communication efficiency in federated learning algorithms. In: 2021 IEEE 24th international conference on computer supported cooperative work in design (CSCWD), pp 552–557. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/CSCWD49262.2021.9437738&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR8" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4807">2021</a>), Luo et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Luo B, Li X, Wang S, Huang J, Tassiulas L (2021a) Cost-effective federated learning design. In: IEEE INFOCOM 2021—IEEE conference on computer communications, pp 1–10. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/INFOCOM42981.2021.9488679&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2641-9874" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR88" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4810">2021a</a>) presented the cost-effective design and evaluating cost-effectiveness for reducing communication costs in federated learning. In the decentralized environment, as the number of edge participants increases, the communication cost also increases significantly due to devices being located in different geo-locations. To address this issue, 2D-Ring network and 2D-attention-based parameter synchronization and device placement algorithms were introduced (Zong et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2024" title="Zong R, Qin Y, Wu F, Tang Z, Li K (2024) Fedcs: efficient communication scheduling in decentralized federated learning. Inf Fusion 102:102028" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR195" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4814">2024</a>) to reduce the communication overhead in decentralized, federated learning. The summary of communication cost management methods are presented in Table <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="table anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Tab8">8</a></p><p><b>Discussion</b> Due to the huge number of parameters and the continuous updating in federated learning, a huge number of updates are required from the clients to the server and from the server to the clients. This in turn increases communication cost and throughput, thereby shooting up the overall energy requirements. To avoid these issues, effective communication methods are paramount. Various researchers have considered irrelevant updates (WANG et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Wang L, Wang W, Li B (2019) CMFL: mitigating communication overhead for federated learning. In: 2019 IEEE 39th international conference on distributed computing systems (ICDCS), pp 954–964. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICDCS.2019.00099&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2575-8411" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR144" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4824">2019</a>), communication bottleneck problems (Rothchild et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Rothchild D, Panda A, Ullah E, Ivkin N, Stoica I, Braverman V, Gonzalez J, Arora R (2020) FetchSGD: communication-efficient federated learning with sketching. In: Proceedings of the 37th international conference on machine learning, pp 8253–8265. PMLR. ISSN: 2640-3498. &#xA;                  https://proceedings.mlr.press/v119/rothchild20a.html&#xA;                  &#xA;                 Accessed 9 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR125" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4827">2020</a>; Liu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022a" title="Liu S, Yu J, Deng X, Wan S (2022a) FedCPF: an efficient-communication federated learning approach for vehicular edge computing in 6G communication networks. IEEE Trans Intell Transp Syst 23(2):1616–1629. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TITS.2021.3099368&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR82" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4830">2022a</a>), and have reduced the upstream and downstream communication costs (Xu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022a" title="Xu J, Du W, Jin Y, He W, Cheng R (2022a) Ternary compression for communication-efficient federated learning. IEEE Trans Neural Netw Learn Syst 33(3):1162–1176. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TNNLS.2020.3041185&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR158" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4833">2022a</a>; Li et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Li C, Li G, Varshney PK (2021b) Communication-efficient federated learning based on compressed sensing. IEEE Internet Things J 8(20):15531–15541. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2021.3073112&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR66" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4836">2021b</a>). In addition, improvements in convergence speed, effective resource allocation for reducing communication cost and different communication conditions have also been considered to reduce the overall communication cost in federated learning.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Applications and functionalities of federated learning"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec8-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec8"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">8 </span>Applications and functionalities of federated learning</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec8-content"><p>In this section, the various design functionalities of federated learning and how they have been incorporated into different applications in general have been examined closely. Upon some scrutiny, it is evident that sectors like healthcare sectors, industry, insurance, and smart city applications have been early adopters of federated learning. A glimpse of various applications related to federated learning have been provided in the following references (Zhou et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Zhou J, Zhang S, Lu Q, Dai W, Chen M, Liu X, Pirttikangas S, Shi Y, Zhang W, Herrera-Viedma E (2021) A survey on federated learning and its applications for accelerating industrial Internet of Things. &#xA;                  arXiv:2104.10501&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 1 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR191" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4847">2021</a>; Zheng et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Zheng Z, Zhou Y, Sun Y, Wang Z, Liu B, Li K (2022) Applications of federated learning in smart cities: recent advances, taxonomy, and open challenges. Connect Sci 34(1):1–28. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1080/09540091.2021.1936455&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR187" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4850">2022</a>; Nguyen et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022b" title="Nguyen DC, Pham Q-V, Pathirana PN, Ding M, Seneviratne A, Lin Z, Dobre O, Hwang W-J (2022b) Federated learning for smart healthcare: a survey. ACM Comput Surv 55(3):60–16037. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3501296&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR102" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4853">2022b</a>; Prayitno Shyu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Prayitno Shyu C-R, Putra KT, Chen H-C, Tsai Y-Y, Hossain KSMT, Jiang W, Shae Z-Y (2021) A systematic review of federated learning in the healthcare area: from the perspective of data properties and applications. Appl Sci 11(23):11191. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.3390/app112311191&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR113" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4856">2021</a>).</p><p>The federated learning structure prevalent in the intergrated applications is shown in Fig. <a data-track="click" data-track-label="link" data-track-action="figure anchor" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#Fig9">9</a>. The figure illustrates how healthcare record data is usually shared using federated learning (Li <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Li T (2019) Federated learning: challenges, methods, and future directions. Section: educational. &#xA;                  https://blog.ml.cmu.edu/2019/11/12/federated-learning-challenges-methods-and-future-directions/&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 14 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR63" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4865">2019</a>). The authors of Xu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Xu J, Glicksberg BS, Su C, Walker P, Bian J, Wang F (2021a) Federated learning for healthcare informatics. J Healthc Inform Res 5(1):1–19. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/s41666-020-00082-4&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR156" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4868">2021a</a>), Nguyen et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022b" title="Nguyen DC, Pham Q-V, Pathirana PN, Ding M, Seneviratne A, Lin Z, Dobre O, Hwang W-J (2022b) Federated learning for smart healthcare: a survey. ACM Comput Surv 55(3):60–16037. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1145/3501296&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR102" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4871">2022b</a>) presented a brief literature about how electronic records are shared across the hospital administration. Similarly, the author of Rieke et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Rieke N, Hancox J, Li W, Milletarì F, Roth HR, Albarqouni S, Bakas S, Galtier MN, Landman BA, Maier-Hein K, Ourselin S, Sheller M, Summers RM, Trask A, Xu D, Baust M, Cardoso MJ (2020) The future of digital health with federated learning. NPJ Digit Med 3:119. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1038/s41746-020-00323-1&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR123" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4874">2020</a>) presented a picture of the future of digital health and highlighted pertinent challenges with respect to using federated learning. In a similar vein, the authors of Qayyum et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Qayyum A, Ahmad K, Ahsan MA, Al-Fuqaha A, Qadir J (2021) Collaborative federated learning for healthcare: multi-modal COVID-19 diagnosis at the edge. &#xA;                  arXiv:2101.07511&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 14 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR115" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4878">2021</a>) presented a clustered learning framework for diagnosing COVID-19 using a remote healthcare centre without sharing sensitive data. However, none of these endeavours have chosen to focus on the selection criteria for data and other functionalities of federated learning. Rather, the authors (Yuan et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020a" title="Yuan B, Ge S, Xing W (2020a) A federated learning framework for healthcare IoT devices. &#xA;                  arXiv:2005.05083&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 14 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR171" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4881">2020a</a>; Choudhury et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Choudhury O, Gkoulalas-Divanis A, Salonidis T, Sylla I, Park Y, Hsu G, Das A (2020) Differential Privacy-enabled federated learning for sensitive health data. &#xA;                  arXiv:1910.02578&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 14 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR25" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4884">2020</a>; Li et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022a" title="Li J, Meng Y, Ma L, Du S, Zhu H, Pei Q, Shen X (2022a) A federated learning based privacy-preserving smart healthcare system. IEEE Trans Ind Inform 18(3):2021–2031. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TII.2021.3098010&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR67" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4887">2022a</a>) chose to present how federated learning is incorporated into the IoT framework and is used to manage the accuracy and communication between the server and decentralized clients. In another instance, the authors of Arikumar et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Arikumar KS, Prathiba SB, Alazab M, Gadekallu TR, Pandya S, Khan JM, Moorthy RS (2022) FL-PMI: federated learning-based person movement identification through wearable devices in smart healthcare systems. Sensors 22(4):1377. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.3390/s22041377&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR7" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4890">2022</a>), Chen et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Chen Y, Wang J, Yu C, Gao W, Qin X (2021b) FedHealth: a federated transfer learning framework for wearable healthcare. &#xA;                  arXiv:1907.09173&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 14 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR19" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4893">2021b</a>) proposed a federated learning-based healthcare monitoring system using wearable devices. In this approach, unlabelled data was recovered from wearable devices and was then incorporated into the labelled data and then processed as per subsequent medical processes.</p><div class="c-article-section__figure js-c-reading-companion-figures-item" data-test="figure" data-container-section="figure" id="figure-9" data-title="Fig. 9"><figure><figcaption><b id="Fig9" class="c-article-section__figure-caption" data-test="figure-caption-text">Fig. 9</b></figcaption><div class="c-article-section__figure-content"><div class="c-article-section__figure-item"><picture class="c-article-section__figure-picture"><source type="image/webp" srcset="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig9_HTML.png?as=webp"><img aria-describedby="figure-9-desc" src="//media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1007%2Fs10462-024-10969-y/MediaObjects/10462_2024_10969_Fig9_HTML.png" alt="Fig. 9" loading="lazy" width="685" height="725"></picture><div class="c-article-section__figure-link"><a class="c-article__pill-button" data-test="article-link" data-track="click" data-track-label="button" data-track-action="view figure" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y/figures/9" data-track-dest="link:Figure9 Full size image" aria-label="Full size image figure 9" rel="nofollow"><span>Full size image</span><svg width="16" height="16" focusable="false" role="img" aria-hidden="true" class="u-icon"><use xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="#icon-eds-i-chevron-right-small"></use></svg></a></div></div><div class="c-article-section__figure-description" data-test="bottom-caption" id="figure-9-desc"><p>Integrated applications of federated learning</p></div></div></figure></div><p>The authors of Hiessl et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Hiessl T, Rezapour Lakani S, Kemnitz J, Schall D, Schulte S (2022) Cohort-based federated learning services for industrial collaboration on the edge. J Parallel Distrib Comput 167:64–76. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jpdc.2022.04.021&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR41" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4918">2022</a>, <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Hiessl T, Schall D, Kemnitz J, Schulte S (2020) Industrial federated learning—requirements and system design. In: De La Prieta F, Mathieu P, Rincón Arango JA, El Bolock A, Del Val E, Jordán Prunera J, Carneiro J, Fuentes R, Lopes F, Julian V (eds) Highlights in practical applications of agents, multi-agent systems, and trust-worthiness. The PAAMS collection. Communications in Computer and Information Science. Springer, Cham, pp 42–53. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-51999-5_4&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR42" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4921">2020</a>), Savazzi et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Savazzi S, Nicoli M, Bennis M, Kianoush S, Barbieri L (2021) Opportunities of federated learning in connected, cooperative, and automated industrial systems. IEEE Commun Mag 59(2):16–21. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/MCOM.001.2000200&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR127" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4924">2021</a>), Nguyen et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Nguyen DC, Ding M, Pathirana PN, Seneviratne A, Li J, Niyato D, Poor HV (2021b) Federated learning for industrial Internet of Things in future industries. IEEE Wirel Commun 28(6):192–199. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/MWC.001.2100102&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR100" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4927">2021b</a>), Wang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Wang J, Xu G, Lei W, Gong L, Zheng X, Liu S (2022) CPFL: an effective secure cognitive personalized federated learning mechanism for industry 4.0. IEEE Trans Ind Inform 18(10):7186–7195. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TII.2022.3150324&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR140" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4930">2022</a>) referred to the present industrial applications that use federated learning. The authors describe the industrial federated system design and the requirements (Hiessl et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Hiessl T, Schall D, Kemnitz J, Schulte S (2020) Industrial federated learning—requirements and system design. In: De La Prieta F, Mathieu P, Rincón Arango JA, El Bolock A, Del Val E, Jordán Prunera J, Carneiro J, Fuentes R, Lopes F, Julian V (eds) Highlights in practical applications of agents, multi-agent systems, and trust-worthiness. The PAAMS collection. Communications in Computer and Information Science. Springer, Cham, pp 42–53. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-51999-5_4&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR42" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4934">2020</a>) and exchanges of data that take place without sharing private data. The authors described the different industrial requirements such as machine type, environmental conditions, and operational conditions under which the federated learning cohorts need to operate in terms of establishing and updating the learning tasks. In such cases, the FLaaS has been used to create industrial client devices. Using industrial federated learning, clients work on a demand basis, while the architecture works on an independent structure of ML models and manages non-IID data using cohorts. The FlaaS supports the above conditions. The authors of Wang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Wang J, Xu G, Lei W, Gong L, Zheng X, Liu S (2022) CPFL: an effective secure cognitive personalized federated learning mechanism for industry 4.0. IEEE Trans Ind Inform 18(10):7186–7195. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TII.2022.3150324&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR140" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4937">2022</a>) proposed industrial personalized federated learning for collaboration between more relevant devices. Federated learning enabled better balance between self-learning and collaborative learning and produced better heterogeneous data for personalization. The authors of Savazzi et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Savazzi S, Nicoli M, Bennis M, Kianoush S, Barbieri L (2021) Opportunities of federated learning in connected, cooperative, and automated industrial systems. IEEE Commun Mag 59(2):16–21. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/MCOM.001.2000200&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR127" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4940">2021</a>), Nguyen et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Nguyen DC, Ding M, Pathirana PN, Seneviratne A, Li J, Niyato D, Poor HV (2021b) Federated learning for industrial Internet of Things in future industries. IEEE Wirel Commun 28(6):192–199. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/MWC.001.2100102&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR100" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4943">2021b</a>) presented the future industrial uses with respect to federated learning. The authors additionally contributed to an understanding of how industrial systems are connected and can cooperate in an automated way to share knowledge and information. The authors of Zheng et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Zheng Z, Zhou Y, Sun Y, Wang Z, Liu B, Li K (2022) Applications of federated learning in smart cities: recent advances, taxonomy, and open challenges. Connect Sci 34(1):1–28. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1080/09540091.2021.1936455&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR187" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4946">2022</a>), Ramu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Ramu SP, Boopalan P, Pham Q-V, Maddikunta PKR, Huynh-The T, Alazab M, Nguyen TT, Gadekallu TR (2022) Federated learning enabled digital twins for smart cities: concepts, recent advances, and future directions. Sustain Cities Soc 79:103663. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.scs.2021.103663&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR120" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4949">2022</a>), Jiang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Jiang JC, Kantarci B, Oktug S, Soyata T (2020) Federated learning in smart city sensing: challenges and opportunities. Sensors 20(21):6230. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.3390/s20216230&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR52" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4953">2020</a>) discussed various areas and challenges prevalent in smart cities. In particular, the authors’ integrated vehicle system and its corresponding autonomous, communication, and how the incentives were integrated into federated learning were examined. To manage the unlabelled data in smart cities, the authors of Albaseer et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Albaseer A, Ciftler BS, Abdallah M, Al-Fuqaha A (2020) Exploiting unlabeled data in smart cities using federated edge learning. In: 2020 international wireless communications and mobile computing (IWCMC), pp 1666–1671. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/IWCMC48107.2020.9148475&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2376-6506" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR3" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4956">2020</a>) proposed a model called Fedsem. Using this work, the labelled data was trained in a global model and injected with unlabelled data into the clients. The authors of Chhikara et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Chhikara P, Tekchandani R, Kumar N, Tanwar S, Rodrigues JJPC (2021) Federated learning for air quality index prediction using UAV swarm networks. In: 2021 IEEE global communications conference (GLOBECOM), pp 1–6. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/GLOBECOM46510.2021.9685991&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR21" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4959">2021</a>) proposed the prediction of an Air Quality Index with data privacy to measure the performance of AQI with security features, using UAVs with Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) and Federated Learning. The authors of Liu et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021a" title="Liu Y, Nie J, Li X, Ahmed SH, Lim WYB, Miao C (2021a) Federated learning in the sky: aerial-ground air quality sensing framework with UAV swarms. IEEE Internet Things J 8(12):9827–9837. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2020.3021006&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR81" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4962">2021a</a>) presented the limitations of the lack of mobility, the crowdsourcing-based monitoring method, and 2-D monitoring using Graph CNN-based long short-term memory (GCLSTM) model with Dense-MobileNet (DM) and Federated Learning techniques to overcome the limitations.</p><p>The authors of Long et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Long G, Tan Y, Jiang J, Zhang C (2020) Federated learning for open banking. In: Yang, Q, Fan, L, Yu, H (eds) Federated learning: privacy and incentive. Lecture Notes in Computer Science. Springer, Cham, pp 240–254. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-63076-8_17&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 14 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR87" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4969">2020</a>), Shingi (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Shingi G (2020) A federated learning based approach for loan defaults prediction. In: 2020 international conference on data mining workshops (ICDMW), pp 362–368. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICDMW51313.2020.00057&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2375-9259" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR130" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4972">2020</a>), Yang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019b" title="Yang W, Zhang Y, Ye K, Li L, Xu C-Z (2019b) FFD: a federated learning based method for credit card fraud detection. In: Chen K, Seshadri S, Zhang L-J (eds) Big Data—BigData 2019. Lecture Notes in Computer Science. Springer, Cham, pp 18–32. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-23551-2_2&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR163" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4975">2019b</a>) presented how federated learning has been used in finance. The authors of Long et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Long G, Tan Y, Jiang J, Zhang C (2020) Federated learning for open banking. In: Yang, Q, Fan, L, Yu, H (eds) Federated learning: privacy and incentive. Lecture Notes in Computer Science. Springer, Cham, pp 240–254. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-63076-8_17&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 14 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR87" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4978">2020</a>) presented the management of non-IID data and personalized modelling in the open bank. The authors of Yang et al. (<a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019b" title="Yang W, Zhang Y, Ye K, Li L, Xu C-Z (2019b) FFD: a federated learning based method for credit card fraud detection. In: Chen K, Seshadri S, Zhang L-J (eds) Big Data—BigData 2019. Lecture Notes in Computer Science. Springer, Cham, pp 18–32. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-23551-2_2&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR163" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e4981">2019b</a>) proposed a federated learning-based credit card fraud detection model using the shared global models across different banks. The shared model was used to make predictions without sharing the cardholder’s data. Compared to the traditional models, this model was found to achieve 10% better accuracy.</p><p><b>Discussion</b> The different applications used federated learning concepts for processing data in a decentralized way with privacy protection. In applications, the data was dynamically changed based on the time series. Dynamic data management in federated learning has potential for further research. More specifically, most of the applications’ client selection criteria, aggregation conditions, and dynamic updating of knowledge sharing in distributed environments have yet to be addressed by researchers.</p></div></div></section><section data-title="Challenges and future direction of research in design of federated learning"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec9-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec9"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">9 </span>Challenges and future direction of research in design of federated learning</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec9-content"><p>This section presents the challenges and future research direction in federated learning in terms of functionalities such as node selection, node dropping, aggregation, knowledge transfer, non-IID data management, incentives, and communication cost.</p><p><b>Node Selection</b> The potential for further research exists in the area of node selection methods in federated learning used to select the client’s data in distributed data environments. Aspects that require consideration are client data updating methods, quality of data, client selection criteria (Abdulrahman et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Abdulrahman S, Tout H, Mourad A, Talhi C (2021b) FedMCCS: multicriteria client selection model for optimal IoT federated learning. IEEE Internet Things J 8(6):4723–4735. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/JIOT.2020.3028742&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR2" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5002">2021b</a>), homogeneous data (Nishio and Yonetani <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Nishio T, Yonetani R (2019) Client selection for federated learning with heterogeneous resources in mobile edge. In: ICC 2019—2019 IEEE international conference on communications (ICC), pp 1–7. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICC.2019.8761315&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 1938-1883" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR105" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5005">2019</a>), uncertain data management updating protocols (Yoshida et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Yoshida N, Nishio T, Morikura M, Yamamoto K (2020) MAB-based client selection for federated learning with uncertain resources in mobile networks. In: 2020 IEEE Globecom workshops, GC Wkshps, pp 1–6. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/GCWkshps50303.2020.9367421&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR169" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5008">2020</a>), energy management in clients (Zheng et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Zheng J, Li K, Tovar E, Guizani M (2021) Federated learning for energy-balanced client selection in mobile edge computing. In: 2021 international wireless communications and mobile computing (IWCMC), pp 1942–1947. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/IWCMC51323.2021.9498853&#xA;                  &#xA;                . ISSN: 2376-6506" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR188" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5011">2021</a>), client scheduling (Xu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021b" title="Xu B, Xia W, Zhang J, Quek TQS, Zhu H (2021b) Online client scheduling for fast federated learning. IEEE Wirel Commun Lett 10(7):1434–1438. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/LWC.2021.3069541&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR157" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5014">2021b</a>), removal of noise data (Yang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Yang S, Park H, Byun J, Kim C (2022) Robust federated learning with noisy labels. IEEE Intell Syst 37(2):35–43. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/MIS.2022.3151466&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR162" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5018">2022</a>), selection of labelled data on similarly fashioned clients and comparison to nearest clients based on same label (apple to apple comparison).</p><p><b>Aggregation</b> The main goal of the aggregation method is to help increase the learning rate of the global model from distributed clients. Reduction in communication rounds, multi-centre aggregation (Xie et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Xie M, Long G, Shen T, Zhou T, Wang X, Jiang J, Zhang C (2021) Multi-center federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:2005.01026&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR155" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5026">2021</a>), conditions for aggregation (Guha et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Guha N, Talwalkar A, Smith V (2019) One-shot federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:1902.11175&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR34" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5029">2019</a>), robust schemes for aggregation (Pillutla et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Pillutla K, Kakade SM, Harchaoui Z (2022) Robust aggregation for federated learning. IEEE Trans Signal Process 70:1142–1154. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TSP.2022.3153135&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR112" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5032">2022</a>; Yeganeh et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Yeganeh Y, Farshad A, Navab N, Albarqouni S (2020) Inverse distance aggregation for federated learning with non-IID data. In: Albarqouni S, Bakas S, Kamnitsas K, Cardoso MJ, Landman B, Li W, Milletari F, Rieke N, Roth H, Xu D, Xu Z (eds) Domain adaptation and representation transfer, and distributed and collaborative learning. Lecture Notes in Computer Science. Springer, Cham, pp 150–159. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-60548-3_15&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR166" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5035">2020</a>), matching with similar clients prior to aggregation (Wang et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Wang H, Yurochkin M, Sun Y, Papailiopoulos D, Khazaeni Y (2020) Federated learning with matched averaging. &#xA;                  arXiv:2002.06440&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 2 Aug 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR147" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5038">2020</a>), aggregation with similar models (Palihawadana et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Palihawadana C, Wiratunga N, Wijekoon A, Kalutarage H (2022) FedSim: similarity guided model aggregation for federated learning. Neurocomputing 483:432–445. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neucom.2021.08.141&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR108" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5042">2022</a>), asynchronous aggregation (Nguyen et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022c" title="Nguyen J, Malik K, Zhan H, Yousefpour A, Rabbat M, Malek M, Huba D (2022c) Federated learning with buffered asynchronous aggregation. In: Camps-Valls G, Ruiz FJR, Valera I (eds) Proceedings of The 25th international conference on artificial intelligence and statistics. Proceedings of machine learning research, vol 151. PMLR, , pp 3581–3607. &#xA;                  https://proceedings.mlr.press/v151/nguyen22b.html&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR103" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5045">2022c</a>), Effective aggregation rules on the server side (Ding et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Ding J, Tramel E, Sahu AK, Wu S, Avestimehr S, Zhang T (2022) Federated learning challenges and opportunities: an outlook. In: ICASSP 2022—2022 IEEE international conference on acoustics, speech and signal processing (ICASSP). Singapore, Singapore, pp 8752–8756. IEEE. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/ICASSP43922.2022.9746925&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 16 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR28" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5048">2022</a>), and energy consumption during aggregation are some of the pertinent future directions to be considered with respect to aggregation design in federated learning.</p><p><b>Knowledge transfer</b> The main purpose of knowledge transfer is the effective transmission of knowledge for better learning even under varying situations. Promising future directions in knowledge transfer include knowledge distillation (Hinton et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2015" title="Hinton G, Vinyals O, Dean J (2015) Distilling the knowledge in a neural network. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.48550/ARXIV.1503.02531&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Publisher: arXiv Version Number: 1. Accessed 16 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR43" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5056">2015</a>; He et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="He C, Annavaram M, Avestimehr S (2020) Group knowledge transfer: federated learning of large CNNs at the edge. In: Advances in neural information processing systems, vol 33. Curran Associates, Inc., pp. 14068–14080. &#xA;                  https://proceedings.neurips.cc/paper/2020/hash/a1d4c20b182ad7137ab3606f0e3fc8a4-Abstract.html&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Accessed 17 Jun 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR39" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5059">2020</a>), heterogeneous data features and parameter sharing (Diao et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Diao E, Ding J, Tarokh V (2020) HeteroFL: computation and communication efficient federated learning for heterogeneous clients. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.48550/ARXIV.2010.01264&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Publisher: arXiv Version Number: 3. Accessed 16 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR27" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5062">2020</a>), neural architecture for knowledge sharing (He et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="He C, Mushtaq E, Ding J, Avestimehr S (2021) Fednas: federated deep learning via neural architecture search" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR40" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5065">2021</a>), effective gradient updates (Wang and Charles <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Wang J, Charles EA (2021) A field guide to federated optimization. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.48550/ARXIV.2107.06917&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Publisher: arXiv Version Number: 1. Accessed 16 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR143" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5068">2021</a>) and application-wise effective topology development for knowledge sharing. These are some of the most dominant functional points to be considered with respect to knowledge transfer in federated learning.</p><p><b>Data management (Non-IID)</b> In federated learning, data management is used to manage the locally produced data with different or non-uniform data distributions of client participants. Different models have been presented based on different behaviours and requirements of uniform data management. In this context, promising areas of future research include management of privacy during knowledge distillation, management of large client data, data training and probability of data dropping, management of real image data (Luo et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2019" title="Luo J, Wu X, Luo Y, Huang A, Huang Y, Liu Y, Yang Q (2019) Real-world image datasets for federated learning. &#xA;                  arXiv:1910.11089&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Publisher: arXiv Version Number: 3. Accessed 16 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR89" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5077">2019</a>; Hsu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Hsu T-MH, Qi H, Brown M (2020) Federated visual classification with real-world data distribution. In: European conference on computer vision. Springer, New York, pp 76–92" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR45" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5080">2020</a>), feature overlapping between the data and clients (Wu et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020" title="Wu Q, Chen X, Zhou Z, Zhang J (2020) Fedhome: cloud-edge based personalized federated learning for in-home health monitoring. IEEE Trans Mob Comput" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR153" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5083">2020</a>), automated machine learning, as well as the influence of managing the distribution of non-IID (Yuan et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2020b" title="Yuan J, Xu M, Zhao Y, Bian K, Huang G, Liu X, Wang S (2020b) Federated neural architecture search. &#xA;                  arXiv:2002.06352&#xA;                  &#xA;                . Publisher: arXiv Version Number: 5. Accessed 16 Sept 2022" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR172" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5086">2020b</a>; Zhu and Jin <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2022" title="Zhu H, Jin Y (2022) Real-time federated evolutionary neural architecture search. IEEE Trans Evol Comput 26(2):364–378. &#xA;                  https://doi.org/10.1109/TEVC.2021.3099448&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR192" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5089">2022</a>).</p><p><b>Incentive</b> The main purpose of the incentives in federated learning is to train the model with high-quality data for better accuracy with reduced model iterations. The main challenge of such incentives in federated learning is improved performance. The incentive-based method is required to improve the accuracy and reduce the cost based on the practical incentive-based approaches in federated learning (Zeng et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2021" title="Zeng R, Zeng C, Wang X, Li B, Chu X (2021) A comprehensive survey of incentive mechanism for federated learning. arXiv preprint &#xA;                  arXiv:2106.15406&#xA;                  &#xA;                " href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR175" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5097">2021</a>).</p><p><b>Communication Cost</b> The primary goal in this case is to reduce the energy used in the entire communication of federated learning. Based on the main challenge the focus should be centred on finding an effective model for efficient federated learning. The key future research directions therefore include reduced-energy green federated learning, use of different models to reduce the communication rounds between clients and the global model, and an effective uplink model, all of which would contribute to reducing the overall communication cost in federated learning.</p><p><b>Scalability</b> Scalability is essential for real-world scenarios. Scalability challenges of federated learning across diverse and extensive networks can be addressed with various strategies such as managing communication overheads, computational load balancing and resource management, Incentive mechanisms and scalability-focused algorithms. </p><ol class="u-list-style-none">
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">i.</span>
                  
                    <p>Communication overheads can be efficiently reduced by using compression techniques, reducing the waiting time by using asynchronous communication, better bandwidth, designing an effective model with the option to reduce or drop updates, and by increasing the overall model performance (Hafi et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2024" title="Hafi H, Brik B, Frangoudis PA, Ksentini A, Bagaa M (2024) Split federated learning for 6g enabled-networks: requirements, challenges and future directions. IEEE Access" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR37" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5120">2024</a>).</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">ii.</span>
                  
                    <p>The load can be distributed evenly to other nodes to prevent bottlenecks, and tasks can be transferred from overloaded nodes to unused ones, thereby increasing efficiency (Folino et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2024" title="Folino F, Folino G, Pisani FS, Sabatino P, Pontieri L (2024) A scalable vertical federated learning framework for analytics in the cybersecurity domain. In: 2024 32nd Euromicro international conference on parallel, distributed and network-based processing (PDP), pp 245–252. IEEE" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR32" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5134">2024</a>).</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">iii.</span>
                  
                    <p>Incentives mechanisms for participation and contribution to high-quality updates, thereby improving overall quality, e.g., monetary rewards, reputation systems (Zhou et al. <a data-track="click" data-track-action="reference anchor" data-track-label="link" data-test="citation-ref" aria-label="Reference 2023" title="Zhou Y, Shi Y, Zhou H, Wang J, Fu L, Yang Y (2023) Toward scalable wireless federated learning: challenges and solutions. IEEE Internet Things Mag 6(4):10–16" href="/article/10.1007/s10462-024-10969-y#ref-CR189" id="ref-link-section-d18034900e5148">2023</a>).</p>
                  
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="u-custom-list-number">iv.</span>
                  
                    <p>Finally, well-designed algorithms that focus on particular tasks to increase scalability, e.g., FedAvg, Fed Prox and Personalised FL algorithms.</p>
                  
                </li>
              </ol></div></div></section><section data-title="Conclusion"><div class="c-article-section" id="Sec10-section"><h2 class="c-article-section__title js-section-title js-c-reading-companion-sections-item" id="Sec10"><span class="c-article-section__title-number">10 </span>Conclusion</h2><div class="c-article-section__content" id="Sec10-content"><p>Federated learning has ushered in a new era for decentralized machine learning. By virtue of its vast applicability, federated learning has garnered a lot of attention from the technical community in the last four years. Since all application data in Fl are privately computed without sharing, it has found eager adoption and endorsement in multiple areas such as healthcare, banking, smart-cites etc. However, in order to assimilate all its benefits, an effective functional design of federated learning is imperative. In this work, all the necessary functional design requirements in FL such as node selection, reason for dropping nodes, effective aggregation, knowledge sharing, data management and communication cost have been duly addressed and presented.</p><p>Additionally, all recent research work of significance pertaining to the various functional design aspects of federated learning have been summarized in this work with focus on the design function methods, goals, and any related discussion points. It is the hope of the authors that this research article will help shine the light on new directions of research in the design of federated learning which will, in turn, help to develop newer applications in the area. To that end, the future direction of the research along with the inherent challenges have been summarized as well. Some of the important areas that warrant further research are as follows: i. Effective node selection methods that consider appropriate incentives for data quality for better accuracy. ii. Novel conditions required to inhibit unwanted node selection. iii. Aggregation methods that consider local aggregation to decrease communication cost. iv. Knowledge transfer mechanisms that not only consider transmission from the local to the server, but also the transfer of knowledge or weights to local nodes using sub-global or sub aggregation methods to avoid communication cost. v. A new, green federated learning framework that enables communication between the client to global model rounds with a considerably smaller energy footprint for better and more sustainable computing.</p></div></div></section>
                                </div>
                        
                    

                    
                        
                    

                    
                        
                    

                    

